# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: egg-and-spoon-race
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] Partridge published seven editions of his "hugely influential" slang dictionary before his death in 1979.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] The dictionary was "regarded as filling a lexicographical gap" in the English language because it contained entries on words that had long been omitted from other works, such as the *Oxford English Dictionary*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] For the two editions published before the Second World War, obscenity laws prohibited full printing of vulgar words; Partridge therefore substituted asterisks for the vowels of words considered obscene.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] In 1972, an abridgement (by Jacqueline Simpson) of the 1961 edition was published by Penguin Reference Books as *A Dictionary of Historical Slang*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] Following the seventh published edition of *A Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English* in 1969, Eric Partridge had collected new material for another edition until his 1979 death.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] Prior to his death, Partridge "designated a successor", librarian and former military intelligence officer Paul Beale (who had contributed military slang to Partridge's efforts since 1974), and the lexicographical work was continued.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] The Eighth edition of *A Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English* was published by Macmillan as a single-volume work in 1984.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] Beale also published in 1990 a condensed version of the dictionary, titled *Partridge's Concise Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] In 2004, editors Tom Dalzell and Terry Victor published *The New Partridge Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English*, a two-volume update of the dictionary.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] Dalzell and Victor were chosen by the publisher Routledge to update the Partridge dictionary; this edition is, however, completely new and unrelated to the previous versions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/a-dictionary-of-slang-and-unconventional-english] A concise edition was published in 2007.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Scattered details of Aesop's life can be found in ancient sources, including Aristotle, Herodotus, and Plutarch.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] An ancient literary work called *The Aesop Romance* tells an episodic, probably highly fictional version of his life, including the traditional description of him as a strikingly ugly slave (δοῦλος) who by his cleverness acquires freedom and becomes an adviser to kings and city-states.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Older spellings of his name have included *Esop(e)* and *Isope*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Depictions of Aesop in popular culture over the last 2,500 years have included many works of art and his appearance as a character in numerous books, films, plays, and television programs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The earliest Greek sources, including Aristotle, indicate that Aesop was born around 620 BCE in the Greek colony of Mesembria.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] A number of later writers from the Roman imperial period (including Phaedrus, who adapted the fables into Latin) say that he was born in Phrygia.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] By Aristotle and Herodotus we are told that Aesop was a slave in Samos; that his slave masters were first a man named Xanthus, and then a man named Iadmon; that he must eventually have been freed, since he argued as an advocate for a wealthy Samian; and that he met his end in the city of Delphi.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Plutarch tells us that Aesop came to Delphi on a diplomatic mission from King Croesus of Lydia, that he insulted the Delphians, that he was sentenced to death on a trumped-up charge of temple theft, and that he was thrown from a cliff (after which the Delphians suffered pestilence and famine).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Before this fatal episode, Aesop met with Periander of Corinth, where Plutarch has him dining with the Seven Sages of Greece and sitting beside his friend Solon, whom he had met in Sardis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Like *The Alexander Romance*, *The Aesop Romance* became a folkbook, a work that belonged to no one, and the occasional writer felt free to modify as it might suit him." Multiple, sometimes contradictory, versions of this work exist.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The earliest known version was probably composed in the 1st century CE, but the story may have circulated in different versions for centuries before it was committed to writing, and certain elements can be shown to originate in the 4th century BCE.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Scholars long dismissed any historical or biographical validity in *The Aesop Romance*; widespread study of the work began only toward the end of the 20th century.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In *The Aesop Romance*, Aesop is a slave of Phrygian origin on the island of Samos, and extremely ugly.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] After interpreting a portent for the people of Samos, Aesop is given his freedom and acts as an emissary between the Samians and King Croesus.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Later he travels to the courts of Lycurgus of Babylon and Nectanabo of Egypt – both imaginary rulers – in a section that appears to borrow heavily from the romance of Ahiqar.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The story ends with Aesop's journey to Delphi, where he angers the citizens by telling insulting fables, is sentenced to death and, after cursing the people of Delphi, is forced to jump to his death.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] *The Aesop Romance* claims that he wrote them down and deposited them in the library of Croesus; Herodotus calls Aesop a "writer of fables" and Aristophanes speaks of "reading" Aesop, but that might simply have been a compilation of fables ascribed to him.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Various Classical authors name Aesop as the originator of fables.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Sophocles, in a poem addressed to Euripides, made reference to the North Wind and the Sun.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Socrates, while in prison, turned some of the fables into verse, of which Diogenes Laërtius records a small fragment.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The early Roman playwright and poet Ennius also rendered at least one of Aesop's fables in Latin verse, of which the last two lines still exist.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Collections of what are claimed to be Aesop's Fables were transmitted by a series of authors writing in both Greek and Latin.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Demetrius of Phalerum made what may have been the earliest, probably in prose (Αἰσοπείων α), contained in ten books for the use of orators, although that has since been lost.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Next appeared an edition in elegiac verse, cited by the Suda, but the author's name is unknown.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Phaedrus, a freedman of Augustus, rendered the fables into Latin in the 1st century CE.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] At about the same time Babrius turned the fables into Greek choliambics.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] A 3rd-century author, Titianus, is said to have rendered the fables into prose in a work now lost.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Avianus (of uncertain date, perhaps the 4th century) translated 42 of the fables into Latin elegiacs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The 4th-century grammarian Dositheus Magister also made a collection of Aesop's Fables, now lost.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Aesop's Fables continued to be revised and translated through the ensuing centuries, with the addition of material from other cultures, so that the body of fables known today bears little relation to those Aesop originally told.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] With a surge in scholarly interest beginning toward the end of the 20th century, some attempt has been made to determine the nature and content of the very earliest fables which may be most closely linked to the historic Aesop.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Scholars have begun to examine why and how this "physiognomic tradition" developed.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] A much later tradition depicts Aesop as a black African from Aethiopia.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The first known promulgator of the idea was Planudes, a Byzantine scholar of the 13th century who made a recension of *The Aesop Romance* in which it is conjectured that Aesop might have been Ethiopian, given his name.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The notion of Aesop's African origin later reappeared in Britain, as attested by the lively figurine of a negro from the Chelsea porcelain factory which appeared in its Aesop series in the mid-18th century.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In 1876 the Italian painter Roberto Fontana portrayed the fabulist as black in *Aesop Narrates His Fables to the Handmaids of Xanthus*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] When the painting was shown at the Exposition Universelle in Paris in 1878, a French critic was dubious: "Why is M.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Fontana's Aesop ... black as an Ethiopian?
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Nevertheless, in 1932 the anthropologist J.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Driberg, repeating the Aesop/Aethiop linkage, asserted that, while "some say he [Aesop] was a Phrygian ... the more general view ... is that he was an African", and "if Aesop was not an African, he ought to have been;" and in 2002 Richard A.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Lobban Jr. cited the number of African animals and "artifacts" in the Aesopic fables as "circumstantial evidence" that Aesop was a Nubian folkteller.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Popular perception of Aesop as black was to be encouraged by comparison between his fables and the stories of the trickster Br'er Rabbit told by African slaves in North America.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In that mixture of live action and animation, Aesop tells fables that differentiate between realistic and unrealistic ambition and his version there of "The Tortoise and the Hare" illustrates how to take advantage of an opponent's over-confidence.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] On other continents Aesop has occasionally undergone a degree of acculturation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] This is evident in Isango Portobello's 2010 production of the play *Aesop's Fables* at the Fugard Theatre in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Based on a script by British playwright Peter Terson (1983), it was radically adapted by the director Mark Dornford-May as a musical using native African instrumentation, dance and stage conventions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Although Aesop is portrayed as Greek, and dressed in the short Greek tunic, the all-black production contextualises the story in the recent history of South Africa.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] There had already been an example of Asian acculturation in 17th-century Japan.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] There Portuguese missionaries had introduced a translation of the fables (*Esopo no Fabulas*, 1593) that included the biography of Aesop.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] This was then taken up by Japanese printers and taken through several editions under the title *Isopo Monogatari*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Even when Europeans were expelled from Japan and Christianity proscribed, this text survived, in part because the figure of Aesop had been assimilated into the culture and depicted in woodcuts as dressed in Japanese costume.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Ancient sources mention two statues of Aesop, one by Aristodemus and another by Lysippus, and Philostratus describes a painting of Aesop surrounded by the animals of his fables.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] With the advent of printing in Europe, various illustrators tried to recreate this scene.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] One of the earliest was in Spain's *La vida del Ysopet con sus fabulas historiadas* (1489, see above).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Baudoin's *Fables d'Ésope Phrygien* (1631) and Matthieu Guillemot's *Les images ou tableaux de platte peinture des deux Philostrates* (1637).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In England, there was Francis Cleyn's frontispiece to John Ogilby's *The Fables of Aesop* and the much later frontispiece to Godwin's *Fables Ancient and Modern* mentioned above in which the fabulist points out three of his characters to the children seated about him.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Early on, the representation of Aesop as an ugly slave emerged.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The later tradition which makes Aesop a black African resulted in depictions ranging from 17th-century engravings to a television portrayal by a black comedian.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In general, beginning in the 20th century, plays have shown Aesop as a slave, but not ugly, while movies and television shows (such as *The Bullwinkle Show*) have depicted him as neither ugly nor a slave.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Perhaps the most elaborate celebration of Aesop and his fables was the labyrinth of Versailles, a hedge maze constructed for Louis XIV with 39 fountains with lead sculptures depicting Aesop's fables.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] A statue of Aesop by Pierre Le Gros the Elder, depicted as a hunchback, stood on a pedestal at the entrance.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Finished in 1677, the labyrinth was demolished in 1778, but the statue of Aesop survives and can be seen in the vestibule of the Queen's Staircase at Versailles.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In 1843, the archaeologist Otto Jahn suggested that Aesop was the person depicted on a Greek red-figure cup, c.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Paul Zanker describes the figure as a man with "emaciated body and oversized head ... furrowed brow and open mouth", who "listens carefully to the teachings of the fox sitting before him.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Aesop began to appear early in literary works.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The 4th-century-BCE Athenian playwright Alexis put Aesop on the stage in his comedy "Aesop", of which a few lines survive (Athenaeus 10.432); conversing with Solon, Aesop praises the Athenian practice of adding water to wine.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Leslie Kurke suggests that Aesop may have been "a staple of the comic stage" of this era.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The 3rd-century-BCE poet Poseidippus of Pella wrote a narrative poem entitled "Aesopia" (now lost), in which Aesop's fellow slave Rhodopis (under her original name Doricha) was frequently mentioned, according to Athenaeus 13.596.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Pliny would later identify Rhodopis as Aesop's lover, a romantic motif that would be repeated in subsequent popular depictions of Aesop.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Aesop plays a fairly prominent part in Plutarch's conversation piece "The Banquet of the Seven Sages" in the 1st century CE.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Beginning with the Heinrich Steinhowel edition of 1476, many translations of the fables into European languages, which also incorporated Planudes's "Life of Aesop", featured illustrations depicting him as a hunchback.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The 1687 edition of *Aesop's Fables with His Life: in English, French and Latin* included 31 engravings by Francis Barlow that show him as a dwarfish hunchback, and his facial features appear to accord with his statement in the text (p.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The Spaniard Diego Velázquez painted a portrait of Aesop, dated 1639–40 and now in the collection of the Museo del Prado.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The presentation is anachronistic and Aesop, while arguably not handsome, displays no physical deformities.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] It was partnered by another portrait of Menippus, a satirical philosopher equally of slave-origin.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] A similar philosophers series was painted by fellow Spaniard Jusepe de Ribera, who is credited with two portraits of Aesop.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] "Aesop, poet of the fables" is in the El Escorial gallery and pictures him as an author leaning on a staff by a table which holds copies of his work, one of them a book with the name Hissopo on the cover.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The other is in the Museo de Prado, dated 1640–50 and titled "Aesop in beggar's rags." There he is also shown at a table, holding a sheet of paper in his left hand and writing with the other.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] While the former hints at his lameness and deformed back, the latter only emphasises his poverty.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In 1690, French playwright Edmé Boursault's *Les fables d'Esope* (later known as *Esope à la ville*) premiered in Paris.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Sir John Vanbrugh's comedy "Aesop" was premièred at the Theatre Royal in Drury Lane, London, in 1697 and was frequently performed there for the next twenty years.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] A translation and adaptation of Boursault's *Les fables d'Esope*, Vanbrugh's play depicted a physically ugly Aesop acting as adviser to Learchus, governor of Cyzicus under King Croesus, and using his fables to solve romantic problems and quiet political unrest.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In 1780, the anonymously authored novelette *The History and Amours of Rhodope* was published in London.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The story casts the two slaves Rhodope and Aesop as unlikely lovers, one ugly and the other beautiful; ultimately Rhodope is parted from Aesop and marries the Pharaoh of Egypt.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Some editions of the volume were illustrated with an engraving of a work by the painter Angelica Kauffman.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] *The Beautiful Rhodope in Love with Aesop* pictures Rhodope leaning on an urn; she holds out her hand to Aesop, who is seated under a tree and turns his head to look at her.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] His right arm rests on a cage of doves, as he points to the captive state of both of them.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Otherwise, the picture illustrates how different the couple are.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Rhodope and Aesop lean on opposite elbows, gesture with opposite hands, and while Rhodope's hand is held palm upwards, Aesop's is held palm downwards.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] She stands while he sits; he is dressed in dark clothes, she in lighter shades.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] When the theme of their relationship was taken up again by Walter Savage Landor, in the two dialogues between the pair in his series of *Imaginary Conversations*, it is the difference in their ages that is most emphasised.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Théodore de Banville's 1893 comedy *Ésope* later dealt with Aesop and Rhodopis at the court of King Croesus in Sardis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Along with Fontana's *Aesop Narrates His Fables to the Handmaids of Xanthus*, two other 19th-century paintings show Aesop surrounded by listeners.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Johann Michael Wittmer's *Aesop Tells His Fables* (1879) depicts the diminutive fabulist seated on a high pedestal, surrounded by an enraptured crowd.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] When Julian Russell Story's *Aesop's Fables* was exhibited in 1884, Henry James wrote to a correspondent: "Julian Story has a *very* clever & big Subject—*Aesop telling fables* ...
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] He has a real talent but ... carries even further (with less ability) Sargent's danger—that of seeing the *ugliness* of things." Conversely, *Aesop Composing His Fables* by Charles Landseer (1799–1879) depicts a writer in a household setting, handsome and wearing an earring.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The 20th century saw the publication of three novels about Aesop.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Wintle's *Aesop* (London: Gollancz, 1943) was a plodding fictional biography described in a review of the time as so boring that it makes the fables embedded in it seem "complacent and exasperating." The two others, preferring the fictional *Life* to any approach to veracity, are genre works.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Hellman's *Peacock's Feather* (Indianapolis: Bobbs-Merrill, 1931).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Its unlikely plot made it the perfect vehicle for the 1946 Hollywood spectacular, *Night in Paradise*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] A dashing (not ugly) Turhan Bey was cast as Aesop.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In a plot containing "some of the most nonsensical screen doings of the year," he becomes entangled with the intended bride of King Croesus, a Persian princess played by Merle Oberon, and makes such a hash of it that he has to be rescued by the gods.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The 1953 teleplay *Aesop and Rhodope* takes up another theme of his fictional history.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Written by Helene Hanff, it was broadcast on Hallmark Hall of Fame with Lamont Johnson playing Aesop.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The three-act *A raposa e as uvas* ("The Fox and the Grapes" 1953) marked Aesop's entry into Brazilian theatre.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The three-act play was by Guilherme Figueiredo and has been performed in many countries, including a videotaped production in China in 2000 under the title *Hu li yu pu tao* or 狐狸与葡萄.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] The play is described as an allegory about freedom with Aesop as the main character.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] Occasions on which Aesop was played as black include Richard Durham's *Destination Freedom* radio show broadcast (1949), where the drama "The Death of Aesop" portrayed him as an Ethiopian.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] In 1971, Bill Cosby starred as Aesop in the TV production *Aesop's Fables – The Tortoise and the Hare*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/aesop] He was also played by Mhlekahi Mosiea in the 2010 South Africa adaptation of British playwright Peter Terson's musical *Aesop's Fables*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] An **allergy** is an exaggerated immune response where the body mistakenly identifies an ordinarily harmless allergen as a threat.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergic reactions give rise to **allergic diseases** such as hay fever, allergic conjunctivitis, allergic asthma, atopic dermatitis, food allergies, and anaphylaxis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Symptoms of allergic diseases may include red eyes, an itchy rash, sneezing, coughing, a runny nose, shortness of breath, or swelling.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Common allergens include pollen, certain foods, metals, insect stings, medications, and materials, such as latex.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The development of allergies is due to genetic and environmental factors.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The mechanism of allergic reactions involves immunoglobulin E antibodies (IgE) binding to an allergen and then to a receptor on mast cells or basophils, where they trigger the release of inflammatory chemicals such as histamine.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Diagnosis is typically based on a person's medical history.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Further testing of the skin or blood may be useful in certain cases.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Positive tests, however, may not necessarily mean there is a significant allergy to the substance in question.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Early exposure of children to potential allergens may be protective.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Treatments for allergies include avoidance of known allergens and the use of medications such as steroids and antihistamines.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In severe reactions, injectable adrenaline (epinephrine) is recommended.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy, which gradually exposes people to larger and larger amounts of allergen, is useful for some types of allergies such as hay fever and reactions to insect bites.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In the developed world, about 20% of people are affected by allergic rhinitis, food allergy affects 10% of adults and 8% of children, and about 20% have or have had atopic dermatitis at some point in time.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Depending on the country, about 1–18% of people have asthma.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Anaphylaxis occurs in between 0.05–2% of people.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Rates of many allergic diseases appear to be increasing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The word "allergy" was first used by Clemens von Pirquet in 1906.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Many allergens, such as dust or pollen, are airborne particles.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In these cases, symptoms arise in areas exposed to air, such as the eyes, nose, and lungs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] For instance, allergic rhinitis, also known as hay fever, irritates the nose, sneezing, itching, and redness of the eyes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Inhaled allergens can also lead to increased production of mucus in the lungs, shortness of breath, coughing, and wheezing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergic rhinitis can simultaneously occur with other allergic responses such as asthma.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Aside from these ambient allergens, allergic reactions can result from foods, insect stings, and reactions to medications like aspirin and antibiotics such as penicillin.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Symptoms of food allergy include abdominal pain, bloating, vomiting, diarrhea, itchy skin, and hives.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Food allergies rarely cause respiratory (asthmatic) reactions, or rhinitis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Insect stings, food, antibiotics, and certain medicines may produce a systemic allergic response that is also called anaphylaxis; multiple organ systems can be affected, including the digestive system, the respiratory system, and the circulatory system.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Depending on the severity, anaphylaxis can include skin reactions, bronchoconstriction, swelling, low blood pressure, coma, and death.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This type of reaction can be triggered suddenly or have a delayed onset.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The anaphylactic reaction may seem to subside, but may recur over time.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Substances that come into contact with the skin, such as latex, are also common causes of allergic reactions, known as contact dermatitis or eczema.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Skin allergies frequently cause rashes, or swelling and inflammation within the skin, in what is known as a "wheal and flare" reaction characteristic of hives and angioedema.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] With insect stings, a large local reaction may occur as an area of skin redness greater than 10 cm in size that can last one to two days.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This reaction may also occur after immunotherapy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The skin forms an effective barrier to the entry of most allergens, but this barrier cannot withstand everything.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] For example, an insect sting can breach the barrier and inject allergen into the affected spot.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] When an allergen enters the epidermis or dermis, it triggers a localized allergic reaction which activates the mast cells in the skin resulting in an immediate increase in permeability of blood vessels, leading to fluid leakage and swelling in the affected area.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Mast-cell activation also stimulates a skin lesion called the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Then the release of chemicals from local nerve endings by a nerve axon reflex causes the widening of surrounding cutaneous blood vessels, which causes redness of the surrounding skin.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] As part of the allergic response, the body has developed a secondary response that, in some individuals, causes a more widespread and sustained skin swelling.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This usually occurs about 8 hours after the allergen originally comes in contact with the skin.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] When an allergen is ingested, a dispersed form of wheal-and-flare reaction, known as urticaria or hives, will appear when the allergen enters the bloodstream and eventually reaches the skin.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This same skin reactivity allows allergists to test for existing allergies by injecting a small amount of an allergen into the skin, which causes a reaction at the injection site.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Even though these injections are very small and local, they still pose the risk of causing systemic anaphylaxis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Substances that come into contact with the airways may trigger allergic reactions in the nose, sinuses, throat and lungs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergic rhinitis, often referred to as hay fever, is one of the most common airway allergies and is characterized by sneezing, nasal congestion, rhinorrhea and itching of the nose and eyes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Airborne allergens commonly associated with allergic rhinitis include pollen, house dust mites, animal dander and mold spores.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergic reactions involving the lower airways may contribute to allergic asthma, in which exposure to allergens can lead to bronchoconstriction, wheezing, coughing and shortness of breath.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Common triggers include pollen, dust mites, animal allergens and occupational exposures such as flour dust or chemical sensitizers.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Some allergic airway reactions may occur rapidly after exposure, while others develop over several hours.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Severe reactions involving airway swelling may impair breathing and constitute a medical emergency.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) is responsible for distinguishing pathogenic organisms from harmless food proteins and commensal bacteria.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Antigens sampled across the intestinal epithelium are presented by CD103+ dendritic cells, which migrate to mesenteric lymph nodes and promote differentiation of Foxp3+ regulatory T cells (Tregs).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] These Tregs subsequently return to the intestinal lamina propria, where cytokines such as interleukin-10 and transforming growth factor-β (TGF-β) contribute to the maintenance of immune tolerance and suppression of allergic T helper 2 (Th2) responses.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Disruption of these regulatory pathways may contribute to allergic sensitization and the development of food allergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Impairment of the intestinal epithelial barrier, altered antigen processing, inflammation, or reduced regulatory T-cell activity may shift immune responses toward IgE-mediated hypersensitivity.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Such defects in oral tolerance have been associated with increased Th2 polarization, elevated allergen-specific IgE production, and reduced regulatory immune activity.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Environmental and dietary factors, including vitamin D deficiency, infections, antibiotic exposure, and changes in food processing, may also influence allergy development through their effects on gut immunity and epithelial integrity.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The intestinal microbiome is increasingly recognized as an important factor in allergy development.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Early-life alterations in the composition and diversity of the intestinal microbiota have been associated with an increased risk of food allergy and atopic disease.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Commensal bacteria contribute to immune maturation, maintenance of epithelial barrier function, and induction of tolerogenic immune responses.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Reduced microbial diversity and loss of certain bacterial taxa may impair oral tolerance and promote allergic sensitization.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Short-chain fatty acids produced by intestinal bacteria may further support regulatory immune pathways and intestinal barrier integrity.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Sensitization to food allergens may also occur through non-oral routes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Exposure to allergens through damaged skin, particularly in individuals with impaired skin barriers such as those with atopic dermatitis, may predispose to food allergy if oral tolerance has not yet been established.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This has contributed to the hypothesis that the timing, route, and context of allergen exposure influence whether tolerance or allergic sensitization develops.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Research into gastrointestinal immune mechanisms has influenced preventive approaches to food allergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Early introduction of allergenic foods, including peanuts and eggs, during infancy has been associated in some populations with a reduced risk of food allergy, likely by promoting oral tolerance during critical periods of immune development.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Risk factors for allergies can be placed in two broad categories: host and environmental factors.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Host factors include heredity, sex, race, and age, with heredity being by far the most significant.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] However, there has been a recent increase in the incidence of allergic disorders that cannot be explained by genetic factors alone.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Four major environmental candidates are alterations in exposure to infectious diseases during early childhood, environmental pollution, allergen levels, and dietary changes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Dust mite allergy, also known as house dust allergy, is a sensitization and allergic reaction to the droppings of house dust mites.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The allergy is common and can trigger allergic reactions such as asthma, eczema, or itching.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The mite's gut contains potent digestive enzymes (notably peptidase 1) that persist in their faeces and are major inducers of allergic reactions such as wheezing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The mite's exoskeleton can also contribute to allergic reactions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Unlike scabies mites or skin follicle mites, house dust mites do not burrow under the skin and are not parasitic.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Dust mite-proof encasements to mattress, pillow, and duvet prevent chronic contact with allergens.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A wide variety of foods can cause allergic reactions, but 90% of allergic responses to foods are caused by cow's milk, soy, eggs, wheat, peanuts, tree nuts, fish, and shellfish.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Other food allergies, affecting less than 1 person per 10,000 population, may be considered "rare".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The most common food allergy in the US population is a sensitivity to crustacea.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Although peanut allergies are notorious for their severity, peanut allergies are not the most common food allergy in adults or children.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Other allergens may trigger severe or life-threatening reactions and are more common when combined with asthma.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Rates of allergies differ between adults and children.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Children can sometimes outgrow peanut allergies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Egg allergies affect one to two percent of children but are outgrown by about two-thirds of children by the age of 5.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The sensitivity is usually to proteins in the white, rather than the yolk.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Milk-protein allergies—distinct from lactose intolerance—are most common in children.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Approximately 60% of milk-protein reactions are immunoglobulin E–mediated, with the remaining usually attributable to inflammation of the colon.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Some people are unable to tolerate milk from goats or sheep as well as from cows, and many are also unable to tolerate dairy products such as cheese.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Roughly 10% of children with a milk allergy will have a reaction to beef.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Lactose intolerance, a common reaction to milk, is not a form of allergy at all, but due to the absence of an enzyme in the digestive tract.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Those with tree nut allergies may be allergic to one or many tree nuts, including pecans, pistachios, and walnuts.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In addition, seeds, including sesame seeds and poppy seeds, contain oils in which protein is present, which may elicit an allergic reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergens can be transferred from one food to another through genetic engineering; however, genetic modification can also remove allergens.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Little research has been done on the natural variation of allergen concentrations in unmodified crops.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Latex can trigger an IgE-mediated cutaneous, respiratory, and systemic reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The prevalence of latex allergy in the general population is believed to be less than one percent.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In a hospital study, 1 in 800 surgical patients (0.125 percent) reported latex sensitivity, although the sensitivity among healthcare workers is higher, between seven and ten percent.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Researchers attribute this higher level to the exposure of healthcare workers to areas with significant airborne latex allergens, such as operating rooms, intensive-care units, and dental suites.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] These latex-rich environments may sensitize healthcare workers who regularly inhale allergenic proteins.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The most prevalent response to latex is allergic contact dermatitis, a delayed hypersensitivity reaction that manifests as dry, crusted lesions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This reaction usually lasts 48–96 hours.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Sweating or rubbing the area under the glove aggravates the lesions, possibly leading to ulcerations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Anaphylactic reactions occur most often in sensitive patients who have been exposed to a surgeon's latex gloves during abdominal surgery, but other mucosal exposures, such as dental procedures, can also produce systemic reactions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Latex and banana sensitivity may cross-react.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Furthermore, those with latex allergy may also have sensitivities to avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] These people often have perioral itching and local urticaria.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Only occasionally have these food-induced allergies induced systemic responses.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Researchers suspect that the cross-reactivity of latex with banana, avocado, kiwifruit, and chestnut occurs because latex proteins are structurally homologous with some other plant proteins.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] About 10% of people report that they are allergic to penicillin; however, of that 10%, 90% turn out not to be.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Serious allergies only occur in about 0.03%.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] One of the main sources of human allergies is insects.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Insect bites, stings, ingestion, and inhalation can trigger an insect allergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Another non-food protein reaction, urushiol-induced contact dermatitis, originates after contact with poison ivy, eastern poison oak, western poison oak, or poison sumac.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Urushiol, which is not itself a protein, acts as a hapten and chemically reacts with, binds to, and changes the shape of integral membrane proteins on exposed skin cells.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The immune system does not recognize the affected cells as normal parts of the body, causing a T-cell-mediated immune response.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Of these poisonous plants, sumac is the most virulent.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The resulting dermatological response to the reaction between urushiol and membrane proteins includes redness, swelling, papules, vesicles, blisters, and streaking.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Estimates vary on the fraction of the population that will have an immune system response.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Approximately 25% of the population will have a strong allergic response to urushiol.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In general, approximately 80–90% of adults will develop a rash if they are exposed to 0.0050 mg (7.7×10−5 gr) of purified urushiol.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Some people are so sensitive that a molecular trace on the skin can initiate an allergic reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are strongly familial; identical twins are likely to have the same allergic diseases about 70% of the time; the same allergy occurs about 40% of the time in non-identical twins.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergic parents are more likely to have allergic children and those children's allergies are likely to be more severe than those in children of non-allergic parents.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Some allergies, however, are not consistent along genealogies; parents who are allergic to peanuts may have children who are allergic to ragweed.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The likelihood of developing allergies is inherited and related to an irregularity in the immune system, but the specific allergen is not.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The risk of allergic sensitization and the development of allergies varies with age, with young children most at risk.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Several studies have shown that IgE levels are highest in childhood and fall rapidly between the ages of 10 and 30 years.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The peak prevalence of hay fever is highest in children and young adults, and the incidence of asthma is highest in children under 10.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Ethnicity may play a role in some allergies; however, racial factors have been difficult to separate from environmental influences and changes due to migration.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] It has been suggested that different genetic loci are responsible for asthma, to be specific, in people of European, Hispanic, Asian, and African origins.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Some loci, such as PRDM2 and POU2AF1, showed pleiotropic effects linking allergic and autoimmune conditions, suggesting shared inflammatory pathways across epithelial tissues.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Within atopic airway disease specifically, the same review noted that IL-13—produced mainly by activated TH2 cells—is a key driver of eosinophilic airway inflammation and remodeling, acting partly through pathways independent of IgE and eosinophils.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are caused by inappropriate immunological responses to harmless antigens driven by a TH2-mediated immune response.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Many bacteria and viruses elicit a TH1-mediated immune response, which down-regulates TH2 responses.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The first proposed mechanism of action of the hygiene hypothesis was that insufficient stimulation of the TH1 arm of the immune system leads to an overactive TH2 arm, which in turn leads to allergic disease.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In other words, individuals living in too sterile an environment are not exposed to enough pathogens to keep the immune system busy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Since our bodies evolved to deal with a certain level of such pathogens, when they are not exposed to this level, the immune system will attack harmless antigens.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Thus, normally benign microbial objects—like pollen—will trigger an immune response.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] It is used to explain the increase in allergic diseases that have been seen since industrialization, and the higher incidence of allergic diseases in more developed countries.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The hygiene hypothesis has now expanded to include exposure to symbiotic bacteria and parasites as important modulators of immune system development, along with infectious agents.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Epidemiological data support the hygiene hypothesis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Longitudinal studies in the third world demonstrate an increase in immunological disorders as a country grows more affluent and, it is presumed, cleaner.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The use of antibiotics in the first year of life has been linked to asthma and other allergic diseases.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The use of antibacterial cleaning products has also been associated with a higher incidence of asthma, as has birth by caesarean section rather than vaginal birth.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Chronic stress can aggravate allergic conditions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This has been attributed to a T helper 2 (TH2)-predominant response driven by suppression of interleukin 12 by both the autonomic nervous system and the hypothalamic–pituitary–adrenal axis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Stress management in highly susceptible individuals may improve symptoms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergic diseases are more common in industrialized countries than in countries that are more traditional or agricultural, and there is a higher rate of allergic disease in urban populations versus rural populations, although these differences are becoming less defined.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Historically, the trees planted in urban areas were predominantly male to prevent litter from seeds and fruits, but the high ratio of male trees causes high pollen counts, a phenomenon that horticulturist Tom Ogren has called "botanical sexism".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Alterations in exposure to microorganisms is another plausible explanation, at present, for the increase in atopic allergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Endotoxin exposure reduces release of inflammatory cytokines such as TNF-α, IFNγ, interleukin-10, and interleukin-12 from white blood cells (leukocytes) that circulate in the blood.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Certain microbe-sensing proteins, known as Toll-like receptors, found on the surface of cells in the body, are also thought to be involved in these processes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Parasitic worms and similar parasites are present in untreated drinking water in developing countries, and were present in the water of developed countries until the routine chlorination and purification of drinking water supplies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Recent research has shown that some common parasites, such as intestinal worms (e.g., hookworms), secrete chemicals into the gut wall (and, hence, the bloodstream) that suppress the immune system and prevent the body from attacking the parasite.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This gives rise to a new slant on the hygiene hypothesis theory—that co-evolution of humans and parasites has led to an immune system that functions correctly only in the presence of the parasites.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Without them, the immune system becomes unbalanced and oversensitive.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In particular, research suggests that allergies may coincide with the delayed establishment of gut flora in infants.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] However, the research to support this theory is conflicting, with some studies performed in China and Ethiopia showing an increase in allergy in people infected with intestinal worms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Clinical trials have been initiated to test the effectiveness of helminthic therapy with certain worms in treating some allergies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] It may be that the term 'parasite' could turn out to be inappropriate, and in fact a hitherto unsuspected symbiosis is at work.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] These TH2 cells interact with other lymphocytes called B cells, whose role is the production of antibodies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Coupled with signals provided by IL-4, this interaction stimulates the B cell to begin production of a large amount of a particular type of antibody known as IgE.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Secreted IgE circulates in the blood and binds to an IgE-specific receptor (a kind of Fc receptor called FcεRI) on the surface of other kinds of immune cells called mast cells and basophils, which are both involved in the acute inflammatory response.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] At this stage, the IgE-coated cells are sensitized to the allergen.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] If later exposure to the same allergen occurs, the allergen can bind to IgE molecules held on the surface of the mast cells or basophils.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Cross-linking of the IgE and Fc receptors occurs when more than one IgE-receptor complex interacts with the same allergenic molecule and activates the sensitized cell.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This results in rhinorrhea, itchiness, dyspnea, and anaphylaxis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Depending on the individual, allergen, and mode of introduction, the symptoms can be system-wide (classical anaphylaxis) or localized to specific body systems.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Asthma is localized to the respiratory system, and eczema is localized to the dermis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] After the chemical mediators of the acute response subside, late-phase responses can often occur.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This is due to the migration of other leukocytes such as neutrophils, lymphocytes, eosinophils, and macrophages to the initial site.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The reaction is usually seen 2–24 hours after the original reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Cytokines from mast cells may play a role in the persistence of long-term effects.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Late-phase responses in asthma differ slightly from those seen in other allergic responses.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] They are still caused by the release of mediators from eosinophils and remain dependent on TH2 cell activity.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Although allergic contact dermatitis is termed an "allergic" reaction (which usually refers to type I hypersensitivity), its pathophysiology involves a reaction that more correctly corresponds to a type IV hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In type IV hypersensitivity, there is activation of certain types of T cells (CD8+) that destroy target cells on contact, as well as activated macrophages that produce hydrolytic enzymes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Effective management of allergic diseases relies on the ability to make an accurate diagnosis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergy testing can help confirm or rule out allergies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Correct diagnosis, counseling, and avoidance advice based on valid allergy test results reduce the incidence of symptoms and need for medications, and improve quality of life.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] To assess the presence of allergen-specific IgE antibodies, two different methods can be used: a skin prick test or an allergy blood test.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Both methods are recommended, and they have similar diagnostic value.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Skin prick tests and blood tests are equally cost-effective, and health economic evidence shows that both tests are cost-effective compared with no test.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Early and more accurate diagnoses save costs due to reduced consultations, referrals to secondary care, misdiagnosis, and emergency admissions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergy undergoes dynamic changes over time.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Regular allergy testing of relevant allergens provides information on if and how patient management can be changed to improve health and quality of life.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Annual testing is often the practice for determining whether allergy to milk, egg, soy, and wheat have been outgrown, and the testing interval is extended to 2–3 years for allergy to peanut, tree nuts, fish, and crustacean shellfish.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Results of follow-up testing can guide decision-making regarding whether and when it is safe to introduce or re-introduce allergenic food into the diet.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Skin testing is also known as "puncture testing" and "prick testing" since it involves a series of tiny punctures or pricks being placed into the patient's skin.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Tiny amounts of suspected allergens and/or their extracts (*e.g.*, pollen, grass, mite proteins, peanut extract) are introduced to sites on the skin marked with pen or dye (the ink/dye should be carefully selected, lest it cause an allergic response itself).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A negative and positive control are also included for comparison (e.g., negative is saline or glycerin; positive is histamine).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A small plastic or metal device is used to puncture or prick the skin.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Sometimes, allergens are injected "intradermally" into the patient's skin, with a needle and syringe.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Common areas for testing include the inside of the forearm and the back.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] If the patient is allergic to the substance, then a visible inflammatory reaction will usually occur within 30 minutes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] This response ranges from slight reddening of the skin to a full-blown hive (called "wheal and flare") in more sensitive patients, similar to a mosquito bite.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Interpretation of the results of the skin prick test is usually done by allergists on a severity scale, with +/− meaning borderline reactivity, and 4+ representing a large reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Increasingly, allergists are measuring and recording the diameter of the wheal-and-flare reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Interpretation by well-trained allergists is often guided by relevant literature.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In general, a positive response is interpreted when the wheal of an antigen is ≥3 mm larger than the wheal of the negative control (e.g., saline or glycerin).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Some patients may believe they have determined their own allergic sensitivity from observation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A skin test is much better than patient observation for allergy detection.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] If a serious life-threatening anaphylactic reaction has brought a patient in for evaluation, some allergists may prefer to perform an initial blood test before conducting a skin prick test.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Skin testing may also not be possible in patients with widespread skin disease or those who have taken antihistamine within the past several days.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Patch testing is a diagnostic method used to identify substances that cause allergic contact dermatitis through a delayed hypersensitivity reaction.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] During the procedure, small amounts of potential allergens are applied to the skin, usually on the back, using adhesive patches containing standardized allergen preparations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The patches are typically left in place for 48 hours, after which the skin is examined for localized eczematous reactions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Additional readings are commonly performed 72–96 hours after application because allergic contact reactions may develop slowly.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Unlike skin prick testing, which is used to diagnose immediate IgE-mediated allergies, patch testing evaluates delayed type IV hypersensitivity reactions mediated by T cells.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergy blood testing, typically measuring allergen-specific IgE, is a quick test that can be ordered by a qualified healthcare professional.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Unlike skin-prick testing, it is not affected by antihistamines and may be used when skin testing is impractical, such as in people with extensive eczema or other skin disease, in pregnancy, or when there is concern about provoking symptoms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] It can be performed in adults and children, including infants, although results must be interpreted together with the clinical history because sensitisation does not always mean clinical allergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] An allergy blood test is available through most laboratories.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A sample of the patient's blood is sent to a laboratory for analysis, and the results are sent back a few days later.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Multiple allergens can be detected with a single blood sample.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergy blood tests are very safe because the person is not exposed to any allergens during the testing procedure.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] After the onset of anaphylaxis or a severe allergic reaction, guidelines recommend that emergency departments obtain a time-sensitive blood test to measure tryptase levels and assess for mast cells activation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The test measures the concentration of specific IgE antibodies in the blood.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Quantitative IgE test results increase the possibility of ranking how different substances may affect symptoms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A rule of thumb is that the higher the IgE antibody value, the greater the likelihood of symptoms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergens found at low levels that today do not result in symptoms cannot predict future symptom development.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The quantitative allergy blood result can help determine what a patient is allergic to, predict and monitor disease progression, estimate the risk of a severe reaction, and explain cross-reactivity.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A low total IgE level is not adequate to rule out sensitization to commonly inhaled allergens.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Statistical methods, such as ROC curves, predictive value calculations, and likelihood ratios have been used to examine the relationship of various testing methods to each other.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] These methods have shown that patients with high total IgE have a high probability of allergic sensitization, but further investigation with allergy tests for specific IgE antibodies for a carefully chosen set of allergens is often warranted.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Laboratory methods to measure specific IgE antibodies for allergy testing include enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay, radioallergosorbent test, fluorescent enzyme immunoassay, and chemiluminescence immunoassay.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Before a diagnosis of allergic disease can be confirmed, other plausible causes of the presenting symptoms must be considered.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Vasomotor rhinitis, for example, is one of many illnesses that share symptoms with allergic rhinitis, underscoring the need for professional differential diagnosis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Once a diagnosis of asthma, rhinitis, anaphylaxis, or other allergic disease has been made, there are several methods for discovering the causative agent of that allergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Giving peanut products early in childhood may decrease the risk of allergies, and only breastfeeding during at least the first few months of life may decrease the risk of allergic dermatitis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] There is little evidence that a mother's diet during pregnancy or breastfeeding affects the risk of allergies, although there has been some research to show that irregular cow's milk exposure might increase the risk of cow's milk allergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] There is some evidence that delayed introduction of certain foods is useful, and that early exposure to potential allergens may actually be protective.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Following revisions to US and UK pediatric guidelines in 2015 and 2017 that encouraged introducing peanut products to high-risk infants at four to six months of age, one 2025 analysis found a 43% drop in the frequency of peanut allergies, with an estimated 40,000 cases prevented.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] According to that report, some pediatric experts have cautioned that real-world implementation of the guidelines may be inconsistent.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Fish oil supplementation during pregnancy is associated with a lower risk of food sensitivities.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Probiotic supplements during pregnancy or infancy may help to prevent atopic dermatitis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Management of allergies typically involves avoiding the allergy trigger and taking medications to relieve symptoms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy may be useful for some types of allergies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Several medications may be used to block the actions of allergic mediators, prevent cell activation, and degranulation processes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] These include antihistamines, glucocorticoids, epinephrine (adrenaline), mast cell stabilizers, and antileukotriene agents are common treatments of allergic diseases.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Anticholinergics, decongestants, and other compounds thought to impair eosinophil chemotaxis are also commonly used.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Although rare, the severity of anaphylaxis often requires epinephrine injection, and where medical care is unavailable, a device known as an epinephrine autoinjector may be used.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Allergen immunotherapy is useful for environmental allergies, allergies to insect bites, and asthma.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Its benefit for food allergies is unclear and thus not recommended.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Immunotherapy involves exposing people to larger and larger amounts of allergen in an effort to change the immune system's response.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Meta-analyses have found that injections of allergens under the skin is effective in the treatment in allergic rhinitis in children and in asthma.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The benefits may last for years after treatment is stopped.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] It is generally safe and effective for allergic rhinitis and conjunctivitis, allergic forms of asthma, and stinging insects.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] To a lesser extent, the evidence also supports the use of sublingual immunotherapy for rhinitis and asthma.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] For seasonal allergies the benefit is small.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In this form the allergen is given under the tongue and people often prefer it to injections.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Immunotherapy is not recommended as a stand-alone treatment for asthma.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] An experimental treatment, enzyme potentiated desensitization (EPD), has been tried for decades but is not generally accepted as effective.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] EPD uses dilutions of allergen and an enzyme, beta-glucuronidase, to which T-regulatory lymphocytes are supposed to respond by favoring desensitization, or down-regulation, rather than sensitization.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] EPD has also been tried for the treatment of autoimmune diseases, but evidence does not show effectiveness.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A review found no effectiveness of homeopathic treatments and no difference compared with placebo.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The authors concluded that, based on rigorous clinical trials of all types of homeopathy for childhood and adolescent ailments, there is no convincing evidence that supports the use of homeopathic treatments.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The allergic diseases—hay fever and asthma—have increased in the Western world over the past 2–3 decades.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Increases in allergic asthma and other atopic disorders in industrialized nations, it is estimated, began in the 1960s and 1970s, with further increases occurring during the 1980s and 1990s, although some suggest that a steady rise in sensitization has been occurring since the 1920s.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The number of new cases per year of atopy in developing countries has, in general, remained much lower.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Although genetic factors govern susceptibility to atopic disease, increases in atopy have occurred within too short a period to be explained by a genetic change in the population, thus pointing to environmental or lifestyle changes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Several hypotheses have been identified to explain this increased rate.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Increased exposure to perennial allergens may be due to housing changes and increased time spent indoors, and changes in cleanliness may decrease activation of a common immune control mechanisms or hygiene, and exacerbated by dietary changes, obesity, and decline in physical exercise.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The hygiene hypothesis maintains that high living standards and hygienic conditions expose children to fewer infections.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] It is thought that reduced bacterial and viral infections early in life direct the maturing immune system away from TH1 type responses, leading to unrestrained TH2 responses that allow for an increase in allergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Changes in rates and types of infection alone, however, have been unable to explain the observed increase in allergic disease, and recent evidence has focused attention on the importance of the gastrointestinal microbial environment.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] It is speculated that these infections exert their effect by critically altering TH1/TH2 regulation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Important elements of newer hygiene hypotheses also include exposure to endotoxins, exposure to pets and growing up on a farm.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Some symptoms attributable to allergic diseases are mentioned in ancient sources.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Particularly, three members of the Roman Julio-Claudian dynasty (Augustus, Claudius and Britannicus) are suspected to have a family history of atopy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The concept of "allergy" was originally introduced in 1906 by the Viennese pediatrician Clemens von Pirquet, after he noticed that patients who had received injections of horse serum or smallpox vaccine usually had quicker, more severe reactions to second injections.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Pirquet called this phenomenon "allergy" from the Ancient Greek words ἄλλος *allos* meaning "other" and ἔργον *ergon* meaning "work".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] All forms of hypersensitivity were previously classified as allergies, and all were thought to be caused by an improper activation of the immune system.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Later, it became clear that several disease mechanisms were implicated, with a common link to disordered immune system activation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In 1963, a new classification scheme was designed by Philip Gell and Robin Coombs that described four types of hypersensitivity reactions, known as Type I to Type IV hypersensitivity.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] With this new classification, the word *allergy*, sometimes clarified as a *true allergy*, was restricted to type I hypersensitivities (also called immediate hypersensitivity), which are characterized as rapidly developing reactions involving IgE antibodies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] A breakthrough in understanding the mechanisms of allergy was the discovery of the antibody class labeled immunoglobulin E (IgE).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] IgE was simultaneously discovered in 1966–67 by two independent groups: Ishizaka's team at the Children's Asthma Research Institute and Hospital in Denver, USA, and by Gunnar Johansson and Hans Bennich in Uppsala, Sweden.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Their joint paper was published in April 1969.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] Radiometric assays include the radioallergosorbent test (RAST test) method, which uses IgE-binding (anti-IgE) antibodies labeled with radioactive isotopes for quantifying the levels of IgE antibody in the blood.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The RAST methodology was invented and marketed in 1974 by Pharmacia Diagnostics AB, Uppsala, Sweden, and the acronym RAST is actually a brand name.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] In 1989, Pharmacia Diagnostics AB replaced it with a superior test named the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, which uses the newer fluorescence-labeled technology.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p01] The updated version, the ImmunoCAP Specific IgE blood test, is the only specific IgE assay the Food and Drug Administration has approved to quantitatively report to its detection limit of 0.1 kU/L.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] The medical speciality that studies, diagnoses, and treats diseases caused by allergies is called allergology.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] An allergist is a physician specially trained to manage and treat allergies, asthma, and other allergic diseases.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] Becoming an allergist/immunologist requires completion of at least nine years of training.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] After completing medical school and graduating with a medical degree, a physician will undergo three years of training in internal medicine (to become an internist) or pediatrics (to become a pediatrician).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] Internists or pediatricians wishing to focus on the sub-specialty of allergy-immunology then complete at least an additional two years of study, called a fellowship, in an allergy/immunology training program.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] Allergists/immunologists listed as ABAI-certified have successfully passed the certifying ABAI examination following their fellowship.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] In the United Kingdom, allergy is a subspecialty of general medicine or pediatrics.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] After obtaining postgraduate exams (MRCP or MRCPCH), a doctor works for several years as a specialist registrar before qualifying for the General Medical Council specialist register.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] Allergy services may also be delivered by immunologists.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] A 2003 Royal College of Physicians report presented a case for improvement of what were felt to be inadequate allergy services in the UK.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] In 2006, the House of Lords convened a subcommittee.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] It concluded likewise in 2007 that allergy services were insufficient to deal with what the Lords referred to as an "allergy epidemic" and its social cost; it made several recommendations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/allergy-p02] Low-allergen foods are being developed, as are improvements in skin prick test predictions; evaluation of the atopy patch test, wasp sting outcomes predictions, a rapidly disintegrating epinephrine tablet, and anti-IL-5 for eosinophilic diseases.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Modern organized sports developed in the 19th century, with the United Kingdom and the United States taking the lead.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Sporting culture was especially strong in private schools and universities, and the upper and middle-class men who attended those institutions played as amateurs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Opportunities for working classes to participate in sport were restricted by their long six-day work weeks and Sunday Sabbatarianism.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In the UK, the Factory Act 1844 gave working men half a day off, making the opportunity to take part in sport more widely available.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Working class sportsmen found it hard to play top level sport due to having to turn up for work.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] On occasion, cash prizes, particularly in individual competitions, could make up the difference; some competitors also wagered on the outcomes of their matches.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] As professional teams developed, some clubs were willing to make "broken time" payments to players, i.e., to pay top sportsmen to take time off work, and as attendances increased, paying men to concentrate on their sport full-time became feasible.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Proponents of the amateur ideal deplored the influence of money and the effect it has on sports.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] It was claimed that it is in the interest of the professional to receive the highest amount of pay possible per unit of performance, not to perform to the highest standard possible where this does not bring additional benefit.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Working class sportsmen did not see why they should not be paid to play.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Hence there were competing interests between those who wished sport to be open to all and those who feared that professionalism would destroy the "Corinthian spirit", summed up as "sportsmanship, fair play, [and] playing for the love of the game".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] This conflict played out over the course of more than one hundred years.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The "Corinthian ideal" of the gentleman amateur developed alongside muscular Christianity in late Victorian Britain, and has been analysed as a historical social phenomenon since the later 20th century.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The Corinthian Football Club founded in 1882 was the paragon of this.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] By the early 21st century the Olympic Games and all the major team sports accepted professional competitors.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, there are still some sports which maintain a distinction between amateur and professional status with separate competitive leagues.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The most prominent of these are golf and boxing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In particular, only amateur boxers could compete at the Olympics up to 2016.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Problems can arise for amateur sportsmen when sponsors offer to help with an amateur's playing expenses in the hope of striking lucrative endorsement deals with them in case they become professionals at a later date.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] This practice, dubbed "**shamateurism**", a portmanteau of *sham* and *amateur*, was present as early as in the 19th century.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] As financial and political stakes in high-level were becoming higher, shamateurism became all the more widespread, reaching its peak in the 1970s and 1980s, when the International Olympic Committee started moving towards acceptance of professional athletes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The advent of the state-sponsored "full-time amateur athlete" of the Eastern Bloc countries further eroded the ideology of the pure amateur, as it put the self-financed amateurs of the Western countries at a disadvantage.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The Soviet Union entered teams of athletes who were all nominally students, soldiers, or working in a profession, but many of whom were in reality paid by the state to train on a full-time basis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] team (with their male coaches in background) posing with their trophy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] manoeuvre under the watchful eyes of her coach.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] All North American university sports are (generally) conducted by amateurs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Even the most commercialized college sports, such as NCAA football and basketball, do not financially compensate competitors, although coaches and trainers generally are paid.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] College football coaches in Texas and other states are often the highest-paid state employees, with some drawing salaries of over five million US dollars annually.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Athletic scholarship programs, unlike academic scholarship programs, cannot cover more than the cost of food, housing, tuition, and other university-related expenses.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In order to ensure that the rules are not circumvented, stringent rules restrict gift-giving during the recruitment process as well as during and even after a collegiate athlete's career; college athletes also cannot endorse products, which some may consider a violation of free speech rights.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Some have criticized this system as exploitative; prominent university athletics programs are major commercial endeavors, and can easily rake in millions of dollars in profit during a successful season.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] College athletes spend a great deal of time "working" for the university, and earn nothing from it at the time aside from scholarships sometimes worth tens of thousands of dollars; basketball and football coaches, meanwhile, earn salaries that can compare with those of professional teams' coaches.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] They also point out that athletic scholarships allow many young men and women who would otherwise be unable to afford to go to college, or would not be accepted, to get a quality education.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Also, most sports other than football and men's basketball do not generate significant revenue for any school (and such teams are often essentially funded by football, basketball, and donations), so it may not be possible to pay athletes in all sports.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Allowing pay in some sports but not others could result in the violation of U.S. laws such as Title IX.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Through most of the 20th century the Olympics allowed only amateur athletes to participate and this amateur code was strictly enforced – Jim Thorpe was stripped of track and field medals for having taken expense money for playing baseball in 1912.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Later on, the nations of the Communist Bloc entered teams of Olympians who were all nominally students, soldiers, or working in a profession, but many of whom were in reality paid by the state to train on a full-time basis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Near the end of the 1960s, the Canadian Amateur Hockey Association (CAHA) felt their amateur players could no longer be competitive against the Soviet team's full-time athletes and the other constantly improving European teams.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] They pushed for the ability to use players from professional leagues but met opposition from the International Ice Hockey Federation (IIHF) and the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] At the IIHF Congress in 1969, the IIHF decided to allow Canada to use nine non-NHL professional hockey players at the 1970 World Championships in Montreal and Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The decision was reversed in January 1970 after IOC President Avery Brundage said that ice hockey's status as an Olympic sport would be in jeopardy if the change was made.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In response, Canada withdrew from all international ice hockey competitions and officials stated that they would not return until "open competition" was instituted.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Günther Sabetzki became president of the IIHF in 1975 and helped to resolve the dispute with the CAHA.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In 1976, the IIHF agreed to allow "open competition" between all players in the World Championships.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, NHL players were still not allowed to play in the Olympics, because of the unwillingness of the NHL to take a break mid-season and the IOC's amateur-only policy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Before the 1984 Winter Olympics, a dispute formed over what made a player a professional.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The IOC had adopted a rule that made any player who had signed an NHL contract but played less than ten games in the league eligible.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, the United States Olympic Committee maintained that any player contracted with an NHL team was a professional and therefore not eligible to play.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The IOC held an emergency meeting that ruled NHL-contracted players were eligible, as long as they had not played in any NHL games.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] This made five players on Olympic rosters—one Austrian, two Italians and two Canadians—ineligible.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Players who had played in other professional leagues – such as the World Hockey Association – were allowed to play.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Canadian hockey official Alan Eagleson stated that the rule was only applied to the NHL and that professionally contracted players in European leagues were still considered amateurs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Murray Costello of the CAHA suggested that a Canadian withdrawal was possible.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In 1986, the IOC voted to allow all athletes to compete in Olympic Games starting in 1988, but let the individual sport federations decide if they wanted to allow professionals.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The act caused the breakup of the Amateur Athletic Union as a wholesale sports governing body at the Olympic level).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Olympic regulations regarding amateur status of athletes were eventually abandoned in the 1990s with the exception of wrestling, where the amateur fight rules are used due to the fact that professional wrestling is largely staged with pre-determined outcomes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Starting from the 2016 Summer Olympics, professionals were allowed to compete in boxing, though amateur fight rules are still used for the tournament.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] English first-class cricket distinguished between amateur and professional cricketers until 1963.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Teams below Test cricket level in England were normally, except in emergencies such as injuries, captained by amateurs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Notwithstanding this, sometimes there were ways found to give high performing "amateurs", for example W.G.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Grace, financial and other compensation such as employment.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] On English overseas tours, some of which in the 19th century were arranged and led by professional cricketer-promoters such as James Lillywhite, Alfred Shaw and Arthur Shrewsbury, a more pragmatic approach generally prevailed.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In England the division was reflected in, and for a long time reinforced by, the series of Gentlemen v Players matches between amateurs and professionals.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Few cricketers changed their status, but there were some notable exceptions such as Wally Hammond who became (or was allowed to become) an amateur in 1938 so that he could captain England.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Hammond was an example of "shamateurism", in that he was offered a "job" which paid more than he earned as a professional cricketer to act as a company's representative and play cricket.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Amateurs touring abroad could claim more in expenses than professionals were paid.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Smith was a well-salaried secretary – and an amateur captain – of Warwickshire County Cricket Club.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Trevor Bailey at Essex and Reg Simpson at Nottinghamshire were in a similar situation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Professionals were often expected to address amateurs, at least to their faces, as "Mister" or "Sir" whereas the amateurs often referred to professionals by their surnames.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Newspaper reports often prefaced amateurs' names with "Mr" while professionals were referred to by surname, or sometimes surname and initials.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] At some grounds amateurs and professionals had separate dressing rooms and entered the playing arena through separate gates.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] An anecdote narrated by Fred Root epitomises the difference between amateurs and professionals: In a match against Glamorgan, the batsmen, Arnold Dyson and Eddie Bates, had collided mid-pitch, and the ball was returned to Root, the bowler.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Root did not break the stumps as both batsmen seemed injured.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] An amateur repeatedly shouted "Break the wicket, Fred, break the wicket!" until Root said: "If you want to run him out, here's the ball: you come and do it." The amateur responded with the words "Oh, I'm an amateur.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] After the Second World War the division was increasingly questioned.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] When Len Hutton was appointed as English national cricket captain in 1952 he remained a professional.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In 1962 the division was removed, and all cricket players became known as "cricketers".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In Australia the amateur-professional division was rarely noticed in the years before World Series Cricket, as many top-level players expected to receive something for their efforts on the field: before World War I profit-sharing of tour proceeds was common.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Australian cricketers touring England were considered amateurs and given the title "Mr" in newspaper reports.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Before the Partition of India some professionalism developed, but talented cricketers were often employed by wealthy princely or corporate patrons and thus retained a notional amateur status.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Women's cricket has always been almost entirely amateur; however, the recent popularity of women's sport has seen many top-level female cricketers become fully professional, with top international players earning up to $300,000 before endorsements and franchise contracts.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Boot money has been a phenomenon in amateur sport for centuries.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The term "boot money" became popularised in the 1880s when it was not unusual for players to find half a crown (corresponding to 12+1⁄2 pence after decimalisation) in their boots after a game.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The Football Association prohibited paying players until 1885, and this is referred to as the "legalisation" of professionalism because it was an amendment of the "Laws of the Game".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, a maximum salary cap of £12 per week for a player with outside employment and £15 per week for a player with no outside employment lingered until the 1960s, even as transfer fees reached over a hundred thousand pounds; again, "boot money" was seen as a way of topping up pay.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Today, the most prominent English football clubs that are not professional are semi-professional (paying part-time players more than the old maximum for top professionals).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Until 2019, when it abandoned amateur status, the most prominent true amateur men's club was probably Queen's Park, the oldest football club in Scotland, founded in 1867 and with a home ground (Hampden Park) which is one of UEFA's five-star stadia.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] They have also won the Scottish Cup more times than any club outside the Old Firm.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Amateur football in both genders is now found mainly in small village and Sunday clubs and the Amateur Football Alliance.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] A peculiar situation took place in the Soviet Union which had Soviet-type economic planning in the country and no non-state enterprises were permitted.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In 1936 the government agency for sports adopted a decision to form competitions for "teams of [football] masters", while at the republican level there were separate competitions among teams from factories and government agencies—players were officially on the payrolls of those institutions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In this way athletes were officially getting paid as workers or officials.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Athletes of the Soviet Armed Forces Sports Society or Dynamo Sports Club (NKVD sports society) carried a rank and a uniform.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The difference between the teams of masters and other teams was that the first competed at the all-Union level and was considered non-amateur, while those at the republican level were considered to be amateur.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The preceding football competitions among cities and regions were phased away.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Around the turn of the 20th century, much of sailing was professionals paid by interested idle rich.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Today, sailing, especially dinghy sailing, is an example of a sport which is still largely populated by amateurs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] For example, in the recent Team Racing Worlds, and the American Team Racing Nationals, most of the sailors competing in the event were amateurs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] While many competitive sailors are employed in businesses related to sailing (including sailmaking, naval architecture, boatbuilding and coaching), most are not compensated for their own competitions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In large keelboat racing, such as the Volvo Around the World Race and the America's Cup, this amateur spirit has given way in recent years to large corporate sponsorships and paid crews.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Like other Olympic sports, figure skating used to have very strict amateur status rules.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In 1992, trust funds were abolished, and the International Skating Union voted both to remove most restrictions on amateurism, and to allow skaters who had previously lost their amateur status to apply for reinstatement of their eligibility.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] A number of skaters, including Brian Boitano, Katarina Witt, Jayne Torvill and Christopher Dean, and Ekaterina Gordeeva and Sergei Grinkov, took advantage of the reinstatement rule to compete at the 1994 Winter Olympics.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, when all of these skaters promptly returned to the pro circuit again, the ISU decided the reinstatement policy was a failure and it was discontinued in 1995.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Prize money at ISU competitions was introduced in 1995, paid by the sale of the television rights to those events.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In addition to prize money, Olympic-eligible skaters may also earn money through appearance fees at shows and competitions, endorsements, movie and television contracts, coaching, and other "professional" activities, provided that their activities are approved by their national federations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The only activity that is strictly forbidden by the ISU is participating in unsanctioned "pro" competitions, which the ISU uses to maintain their monopoly status as the governing body in the sport.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Rugby has provided one of the most visible and lasting examples of the tension between amateurism and professionalism during the development of nationally organised sports in Britain in the late-19th century.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Rugby football, despite its origins in the privileged English public schools, was a popular game throughout England by around 1880, including in the large working-class areas of the industrial north.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, as the then-amateur sport became increasingly popular and competitive, attracting large paying crowds, teams in such areas found it difficult to attract and retain good players.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] This was because physically fit local men needed to both work to earn a wage – limiting the time that they could devote to unpaid sport – and to avoid injuries that might prevent them working in the future.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Certain teams faced with these circumstances wanted to pay so-called 'broken time' money to their players to compensate them for missing paid work due to their playing commitments, but this contravened the amateur policy of the Rugby Football Union (RFU).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Following a lengthy dispute on this point during the early 1890s, representatives of more than 20 prominent northern rugby clubs met in Huddersfield in August 1895 to form the Northern Rugby Football Union (NRFU), a breakaway administrative body which would permit payments to be made to players.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The NRFU initially adopted established RFU rules for the game itself, but soon introduced a number of changes, most obviously a switch from 15 to 13 players per side.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] It became the Rugby Football League in 1922, by which time the key differences in the two codes were well established, with the 13-a-side variant becoming known as rugby league.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The RFU took strong action against the clubs involved in the formation of the NRFU, all of whom were deemed to have forfeited their amateur status and therefore to have left the RFU.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] A similar interpretation was applied to all players who played either for or against such clubs, whether or not they themselves received any compensation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Such players were effectively barred *sine die* from any involvement in organised rugby union.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] These comprehensive and enduring sanctions, combined with the very localised nature of most rugby competition, meant that most northern clubs had little practical alternative but to affiliate with the NRFU in the first few years of its existence.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Rugby football in Britain therefore became subject to a de facto schism along regional – and to some extent class – lines, reflecting the historical origins of the split.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Rugby league – in which professionalism was permitted – was predominant in northern England, particularly in industrial areas, and was viewed as a working class game.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Rugby union – which remained amateur – was predominant in the rest of England, as well as in Wales and Scotland.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Rugby union also had a more affluent reputation, although there are areas – notably in South Wales and in certain English cities such as Gloucester – with a strong working-class rugby union tradition.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Discrimination against rugby league players could verge on the petty – former Welsh international Fred Perrett was once excluded in lists of players who died in the First World War due to his 'defection' to the league code.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] One Member of Parliament, David Hinchliffe, described it as "one of the longest (and daftest) grievances in history" with anyone over the age of 18 associated with rugby league being banned forever from rugby union.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In Wales the position was more equivocal with clubs attempting to stem the tide of players *going north* with *boot money*, a reference to the practice of putting cash payments into player's footwear whilst they were cleaning up after a game.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Rugby union was declared "open" in August 1995 – almost exactly 100 years after the original split occurred – meaning that professionalism has been permitted in both rugby codes since that date.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, while the professional-amateur divide remained in force, there was originally very limited crossover between the two codes, the most obvious occasions being when top-class rugby union players 'switched codes' to rugby league in order to play professionally.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Welsh international Jonathan Davies was a high-profile example of this switch.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Since professionalism has been allowed in rugby union the switches have started to come the opposite way.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Union has swiftly grown to embrace the professional game with many league players joining union to take a slice of the larger amounts of money available in the sport.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Also, some rugby unions have amateur rules, most notably the Argentine Rugby Union, where all member clubs are amateur.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The Campeonato Argentino, the national championship for provincial teams, does not include players contracted to the country's Super Rugby side, the Jaguares.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Alternative sports, using the flying disc, began in the mid-sixties.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] As numbers of young people became alienated from social norms, they resisted and looked for alternative recreational activities, including that of throwing a Frisbee.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] What started with a few players, in the sixties, like Victor Malafronte, Z Weyand and Ken Westerfield experimenting with new ways of throwing and catching a Frisbee, later would become known as playing freestyle.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Organized disc sports, in the 1970s, began with promotional efforts from Wham-O and Irwin Toy (Canada), a few tournaments and professionals using Frisbee show tours to perform at universities, fairs and sporting events.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Disc sports such as freestyle, double disc court, guts, disc ultimate and disc golf became this sports first events.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Two sports, the team sport of disc ultimate and disc golf are very popular worldwide and are now being played semi professionally.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The World Flying Disc Federation, Professional Disc Golf Association, and the Freestyle Players Association, are the official rules and sanctioning organizations for flying disc sports worldwide.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Disc ultimate is a team sport played with a flying disc.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The object of the game is to score points by passing the disc to members of your own team, on a rectangular field, 120 yards (110 m) by 40 yards (37 m), until you have successfully completed a pass to a team member in the opposing team's end zone.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] There are currently over five million people that play some form of organized ultimate in the US.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Ultimate has started to be played semi-professionally with two newly formed leagues, the American Ultimate Disc League (AUDL) and Major League Ultimate (MLU).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The game of guts was invented by the Healy Brothers in the 1950s and developed at the International Frisbee Tournament (IFT) in Marquette, Michigan.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The game of ultimate, the most widely played disc game, began in the late 1960s with Joel Silver and Jared Kass.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In the 1970s it developed as an organized sport with the creation of the Ultimate Players Association with Dan Roddick, Tom Kennedy and Irv Kalb.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Double disc court was invented and introduced in the early 1970s by Jim Palmeri.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In 1974, freestyle competition was created and introduced by Ken Westerfield and Discrafts Jim Kenner.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In 1976, the game of disc golf was standardized with targets called "pole holes" invented and developed by Wham-O's Ed Headrick.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Sports teams commonly exist at the high school level.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Those who participate, commonly referred to as student athletes, do so during their course of study.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In the United States, each state has one or two high school sports associations, which are members of the National Federation of State High School Associations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Over 7 million high school students participate in athletics every year.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Occasionally, success in high school sports may lead to a professional career in the field.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The benefit of sports in high school is debated; some believe that they promote discipline and teamwork, while others find that they can cause injury.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] One study on the relationship between high school athletic and academic successes finds that, for the most part, higher participation and success rates in sports is positively related school-wide student successes on academic outcomes such as standardized test scores and educational attainment.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The National Center for Educational Statistics reports that student athletes have a 20% higher chance of completing a college degree, and are more likely to be employed and in better health than non-athletes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, a survey of high school athletes in 2006 showed that high school athletes are more likely to cheat inside of the classroom than non-athletes, especially boys participating in football, baseball, and basketball and girls participating in softball and basketball.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The survey does not indicate to what extent cheating contributes to the greater academic outcomes of high school athletes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In the world of middle school and high school sports, several fees have risen over the last few years making sports more expensive.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The term "Pay-to-Play" means that students and their parents must pay a flat fee to participate, and that fee often leaves out the costs of uniforms, transportation, and other team fees.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] This affects low-income families (those who earn less than $60,000 per year) and their ability to participate in the sports.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The average cost is $381 per child per sport (Pay-to-Play Sports).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Physical and mental health can improve with the right amount of physical fitness incorporated into everyday life.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] It allows for the child to have a healthy developing body, and a BMI within the normal range.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Physical activity has been proven to improve mood and decrease both stress and anxiety.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Studies have shown that the more physical activity one participates in as a child, the happier and more stable that person will be as an adult.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Thus, the more students who participate in school sports, the more students who will find themselves balanced and successful adults later in life.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In Japan, extracurricular sports activities known as bukatsudo (部活動, club activities) and high school sports are extremely popular.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In Japan, National High-school Baseball Tournament of Japan (全日本高等学校野球選手権), which highest of amateur sports of the Japan and world, that one of very interest in sports item for Japan, when held on every August, and also regional primary event held in every July on nationwide Japan.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] See also High School Baseball (ja:高校野球).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] For Japanese soccer, see High School Soccer (ja:高校サッカー).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] For Japanese high school sports in general, see Club Activities (ja:クラブ活動).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Golf still has amateur championships, most notably the U.S.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Amateur Championship, British Amateur Championship, U.S.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Women's Amateur, British Ladies Amateur, Walker Cup, Eisenhower Trophy, Curtis Cup and Espirito Santo Trophy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] However, amateur golfers are far less known than players of professional golf tours such as the PGA Tour and European Tour.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Still, a few amateurs are invited to compete in open events, such as the U.S.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Open and British Open or non-open event, such as the Masters Tournament.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Amateur golfers that win open tournaments may receive a trophy but are not entitled to any prize money above £700.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In motorsports, there are various forms of amateur drivers.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] When they compete at professional events, they are often referred to as "pay drivers".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] They have been a presence in Formula One for many years – drivers such as Felipe Nasr, Esteban Gutiérrez and Rio Haryanto bring sponsorship to the tune of $30 million for a seat, even in backmarker teams.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In sports car racing, drivers are often seeded into certain categories, including Amateur and Pro-Am classes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The vast majority of these "gentlemen drivers" however tend to participate at club level, often racing historic or classic cars, which are aimed primarily at amateurs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] In Ireland, the Gaelic Athletic Association, or GAA, protects the amateur status of the country's national sports, including Gaelic football, hurling and camogie.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] The GAA sees Croke Park, with a capacity of 82,300 people, filled for the Senior Football and Hurling Championship finals.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Major tennis championships prohibited professionals until 1968, but the subsequent admission of professionals virtually eliminated amateurs from public visibility.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/amateur-sports] Paying players was considered disreputable in baseball until 1869.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] Furman was born in 1954 in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] He was fascinated with the *Guinness Book of World Records* as a child but never thought he could ever break a record since he was very unathletic.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] As a teenager, he became interested in spirituality and in 1970 became a devout follower of the spiritual leader Sri Chinmoy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] Sri Chinmoy inspired Furman to participate in a 24-hour bicycle race in New York City's Central Park in 1978.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] With only two weeks' training, Furman tied for third place, cycling 405 miles (652 km).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] Around this time, he changed his first name to Ashrita ('protected by God' in Sanskrit).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] In 1979, Furman set his first official record by doing 27,000 jumping jacks.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] In 1986, Furman invented and set the record for underwater pogo stick jumping and introduced it on *Good Morning America* on April Fools' Day.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] Furman has managed a health food store in Jamaica, Queens, New York, since 1982.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] He is also a tour manager for his meditation group and is therefore able to travel extensively.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] As of 2014, Furman has set records in 40 countries.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] He completed his goal of breaking a record on all seven continents when he set the mile hula hoop record at Uluru (also known as Ayers Rock) in the Australian desert in 2003.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] While in China, Furman broke the record for running 8 km (4.97 mi) on stilts in the fastest time (39 min 56 sec), a record which had stood since 1982.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] Furman has also been a pioneer in setting records in several new activities including landrowing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] Using a converted indoor rower with wheels and brakes, Furman rowed 1,500 miles (2,400 km) in 16 days in Bali in 1991.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] Furman also developed the sport of gluggling, underwater juggling, which he did for 48 minutes at Kelly Tarlton's Antarctic Encounter and Underwater World in Auckland, New Zealand, in 2002, and distance sack racing, which Furman did for a mile while racing against a yak in Mongolia in 2007.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] On January 30, 2008, Furman unveiled his giant pencil – 76 feet (23 m) long, 22,000 pounds (with 4,000 solid pounds of Pennsylvania graphite).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] The pencil was built in three weeks as a birthday gift for teacher Sri Chinmoy on 27 August 2007.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] Longer than the 65-foot (20 m) pencil outside the Malaysia HQ of stationers Faber-Castell, it was transported from Queens, New York, to the City Museum in St.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/ashrita-furman] In April 2009 Furman became the first person to hold 100 Guinness world records at once.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The length of incubation before the egg is cooked is a matter of local preference, but generally ranges from two to three weeks.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut can cause vomiting if not cooked correctly.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] A balut is a fertilized bird egg (usually a duck) that is incubated for a period of 14 to 21 days, depending on the local culture, and then steamed.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The contents are eaten directly from the shell.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut that is incubated for longer periods have a well-developed embryo and the features of the duckling are recognizable.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The partially developed embryo bones are soft enough to chew and swallow as a whole.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The mallard duck (*Anas platyrhynchus*), also known as the "Pateros duck", is often used to make balut.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut is a renowned dish due to its different developmental stages; some people prefer it when the duck embryo is still largely liquid, while others prefer it when it is more mature and has a chewier texture.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] A combination of savory, gamey, and rich characteristics can be found in the flavor, which makes it an acquired taste that many Filipinos treasure as a culinary treat and a part of their culture.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut is common street food in the Philippines, Vietnam, and other localities, and is also sold in stores and malls.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] It is a relatively cheap source of protein and calcium.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut was introduced to the Philippines by the Chinese in 1565, and since then balut has been included as a traditional part of the culture.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Wherever Filipinos migrated for work, a large market for balut would develop.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Controversies arose as knowledge of the food spread around the Southeast Asian countries and then globally.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] People have questioned the ethics of eating balut.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Ethical concerns are most often attributed to the presence of a fertilized embryo within the dish, given the fact that the egg has not yet hatched nor been given the chance to hatch.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] There are also ethical concerns as to whether the embryos can feel pain at the stages balut tends to be boiled.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Traditionally, the fertilized eggs are incubated in the sun or buried in sand and stored in baskets to retain warmth.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In order for the embryo to develop normally, it must be exposed to heat for the correct period of time while ensuring that the temperature is not too hot to harm the eggs or too cold to permit growth.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The embryo is extremely sensitive to high temperatures and is easily killed upon cooking in the sun.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Within the first few stages of maturation, balut is known as "balut sa puti" ("wrapped in white") when it is white; the embryo inside is insufficiently developed to show a beak, feathers, or claws, and the bones are undeveloped.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] These are made from very specific egg types, less than five days old and with no visible surface cracks.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The duration of egg incubation is a matter of local preference.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In the Philippines, balut is generally incubated for 14 to 18 days before being boiled for consumption.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] At about 14 to 16 days of incubation, the embryo floats on top of the egg white and yolk, and the balut is called "mamatong".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] For most balut makers, the ideal incubation is said to be 17 days old.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In the Cambodian version, *pong tea khon*, the egg is incubated for 18 to 20 days.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In the Vietnamese version, *trứng vịt lộn*, the egg is incubated for 19 to 21 days, when the embryo is old enough to be recognizable as a baby duck and has bones that will be firm but tender when cooked.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] During this cooking process, changes occur in the food chemistry of balut, such as the sol dispersion of water molecules within the embryonic fluid.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] This liquid becomes the broth for the solid which are parts of the duck within the egg.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Although balut mainly consists of protein, fat is present and is emulsified within the fertilized embryo.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] After cooking, it can be considered a protein gel, depending on the length of time it was cooked.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Heating high-protein food such as balut can cause the chemical changes to take place and fully or partially denature proteins, causing the surface to become thick and causing an irreversible gel protein to form.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Temperature has a significant impact on the final taste and texture of the cooked balut.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Warm temperatures of 29–30 °C (84–86 °F) change the taste and texture of the yolk by making it more grainy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] This can be attributed to the changes in proteins, and their partial denaturation, during the heating and incubation process.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] When boiling or cooking eggs, the white of the egg tends to solidify because the proteins are denatured in an irreversible reaction and turn from transparent to an opaque white.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Physical and chemical changes in the final balut product can also be attributed to microbial infections and the rate that microbes infect the balut at various stages.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] There are many chemical changes that occur inside the duck egg as it is being processed, which can vary depending on how or what it is cooked with.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] While boiling, added salt can contribute to a number of chemical changes; it seems to increase the proportional weight of egg white within the shell, which can be due to the weight differences between the embryo and the egg white itself.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Added salt can also increase the hardness of the egg yolk and affect the overall texture of the final balut product.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Other chemical changes observed in nutrient content of the duck egg as it is processed are a slight decrease in the amount of available amino acids, water-soluble vitamins, and minerals after the processing is complete.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] There are different nutritional values for balut, since it can be either fertilized chicken or duck eggs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut nutrition specifications between chicken and duck have minor differences, but both eggs have around 14 grams of crude protein, 188 calories each, and around 100 milligrams of calcium.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] A duck egg might have a higher value of nutrition than a chicken egg, but overall, both chicken and duck balut have approximately the same nutritional value.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In folk medicine, according to popular Vietnamese belief, these eggs are nutritious and restorative food for pregnant or delivering women.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut eggs are savored for their balance of textures and flavors.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The broth surrounding the embryo is often sipped from the egg before the shell is peeled, then the yolk and young chick inside can be eaten.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] All of the contents of the egg may be consumed, although the white albumen may remain uneaten, depending on the age of the fertilized egg.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] This white albumen may have an unappetizing cartilaginous taste and is tough and rubbery in texture.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In the Philippines, balut has recently entered *haute cuisine* by being served as appetizers in restaurants, cooked adobo style, fried in omelettes, or even used as filling in baked pastries.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In Vietnam, balut is eaten with a pinch of pepper salt with lime/kumquat or ginger and rau răm (also known as laksa leaf).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The dish "trứng vịt lộn" can be served as boiled balut or grilled balut.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In Cambodia, balut is eaten while still warm in the shell and served with nothing more than a little garnish, which is usually a mixture of lime juice and ground pepper.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] A similar preparation is known in China as *maodan* (Chinese: 毛蛋; pinyin: *máo dàn*; lit.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] 'feathered egg'), *modan* (Chinese: 末蛋; pinyin: *mò dàn*; lit.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] 'end-stage egg'), *wangjidan* (Chinese: 旺雞蛋; pinyin: *wàng jīdàn*; lit.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] 'flush egg'), or *huozhuzi* (Chinese: 活珠子; pinyin: *huózhūzi*; lit.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Chinese traders and migrants are said to have brought the idea of eating fertilized duck eggs to the Philippines; however, the knowledge and craft of balut-making has been localized by the balut-makers (*magbabalut*).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Today, balut production has not been mechanized in favor of the traditional production by hand.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Many vendors sell cooked balut from buckets of sand (used to retain warmth) accompanied by small packets of salt.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Uncooked balut are rarely sold in Southeast Asia.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In the United States, Asian markets occasionally carry uncooked balut eggs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Alternatively, they can be ordered by mail.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The cooking process is identical to that of hard-boiled chicken eggs, and baluts are eaten while still warm.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Duck eggs that are not properly developed after nine to twelve days are sold as *penoy*, which look, smell, and taste similar to a regular hard-boiled egg.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In Filipino cuisine, these are occasionally beaten and fried, similar to scrambled eggs, and served with a vinegar dip.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut is consumed in high amounts within countries in Southeast Asia, including Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Thailand, and the Philippines.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Pateros is a first-class municipality in metro Manila, Philippines, that is famous for its duck-raising industry and balut production.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The Pateros municipality was actually named for its duck farmers by speakers of Spanish.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut is recognized as a national food of the Philippines.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] It is commonly sold as a street food and served as an appetizer in restaurants.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The taste of balut is similar to chicken soup, and it has an unusual texture.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut is found in some countries and locations of North America.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] While it cannot be found in every store in North America, specialty stores such as T&T — and, in particular, Filipino stores in the Greater Vancouver area — often sell balut.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In the United States, growers such as Metzer Farms specialize in balut production, spreading the knowledge of balut and its awareness.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] One reason it may not be found or consumed as frequently in North America is that the majority of people outside of Southeast Asia still recognize balut as a novel and taboo food and are often anxious about trying it.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In the Philippines, balut is often eaten with salt or a chili, garlic, and vinegar (white or coconut sap) mixture to season, depending on personal preference.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut can be served in many ways and may be cooked, boiled, or fried.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] It may be cooked adobo style, fried in omelets, or used as filling in pastries.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Although balut is globally recognized as a Filipino food, it is being consumed less and less in the Philippines.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] This is partly due to increasingly Western tastes, but also because balut is often associated with poverty.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Some countries and locations will serve balut raw, although this is not a common practice.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] "Raw", in this sense, could mean the balut was lightly boiled or cooked very briefly.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] This is potentially dangerous, since it increases the risk of spoiling and of ingesting harmful microorganisms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In Vietnam, balut (trứng vịt lộn, hột vịt lộn) can be found in the majority of breakfast restaurants selling noodles (often as a side dish), and night street vendors.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] It is boiled and then served in small bowls with salt, chili, pepper and ginger.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut is considered to be a street food, and like many other street foods, it is best consumed as soon as it is prepared and served.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Sources suggest that at most, the shelf life of a cooked balut is one day, but it can last up to a week in the refrigerator.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] According to the FDA Food Code, balut can perish over time or due to temperature changes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] After being cooked, balut should be handled either at 57 °C (135 °F) and above or kept at or below 5 °C (41 °F).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] While most countries have specific regulations and standards for food, Canada has certain egg regulations pertaining to what products can be labelled as an egg.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut eggs are not subjected to the egg regulations in Canada under the Canadian Food Inspection Agency, meaning they do not require the specific labeling requirements and rules of the traditional chicken egg.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Eating balut is forbidden for some religious groups.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Both Judaism and Islam have strict prohibitions on consuming food that is prepared in manners incompatible with religiously prescribed dietary laws.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In Judaism, the embryo of a chick inside an egg of a bird, even a kosher bird, is forbidden for consumption.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The Quran forbids consumption of meat if the animal has not been slaughtered properly, making the animal or animal-product "maytah".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Because balut is an egg containing a partially developed embryo, this makes it "haram", or "forbidden".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Information relating to whether boiling a partially developed embryo is ethically acceptable or not can be found in the legislation relating to the euthanasia and treatment of research animals.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Bird embryos that have reached greater than 50% of their incubation have developed a neural tube sufficient for pain perception; therefore, they should be euthanized by similar methods used in avian neonates, such as anesthetic overdose, decapitation, or prolonged exposure to carbon dioxide.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Similarly, in the UK, embryonic birds are "protected animals" once they have reached the last third of their incubation period.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] There are specified methods of humanely killing protected animals used in research, but boiling is not one of these.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Depending on the species of duck, some eggs used for balut would be boiled within the last half or third of embryo development.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Duck embryos are often taken off incubation in order to stunt the growth process; the embryos no longer develop and become readily available for purchasing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The RSPCA Australia recommends against boiling the duck embryo from the 18th day of incubation onwards due to the potential for suffering beyond that point, and notes that it is "an area that is yet to be further researched".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] A petition has been raised to get 5,000 signatures to have balut labeled "fertilized duck egg with embryo" and taken off the menu in the Maharlika restaurant, New York.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] As of 2014, the restaurant was selling balut for $5 each.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] As a response to this petition, Filipino New Yorkers have created a counterpetition, asking to leave the food item alone.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The incubation temperatures and environment required for the proper development of balut during processing are ideal growth conditions for many bacteria, including *Salmonella enteritidis*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In addition, faecal pathogens can be deposited on the egg shell surface during laying.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Balut is therefore labelled as a "Hazardous Food" in Canada.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Warnings have been published to obtain balut only from safe, well-known producers.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] In the United States, eggs are sold at Asian markets.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] However, to get the right age eggs and to ensure freshness, it is recommended that they be purchased from a professional or an egg vendor at Asian farmers markets.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] On April 10, 2015, former Pateros mayor Jaime C.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] Medina collaborated with the Center for Culinary Arts (CCA, Manila) and the History Channel to attempt to set the record for the world's largest serving of balut in Pateros, Metro Manila.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The CCA chefs, headed by Tristan Encarnacion, prepared 1,000 pieces of balut into an adobo dish that was recorded to have weighed 117.5 kilograms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The resulting dish was enjoyed by the townsfolk in a symbolic boodle fight, with tables topped with banana leaves stretching along B.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/balut-food] The 2024 horror video game *Hapunan* has the player taking on the role of Niko, a poor Filipino student who sells balut in Barangay Sak Dudol, where a gang of contract killers is suspected of committing brutal murders during the night.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The **British Broadcasting Corporation** (**BBC**) is a British public service broadcaster that serves as the primary national public broadcasting company of the United Kingdom, headquartered at Broadcasting House in London, England.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Originally established in 1922 as the British Broadcasting Company, it evolved into its current state with its current name on 1 January 1927.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] It is the oldest and largest local and global broadcaster by stature and by number of employees, with a total staff of 21,000.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC was established under a royal charter, and operates under an agreement with the secretary of state for culture, media and sport.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Its work is funded principally by an annual television licence fee which is charged to all British households, companies, and organisations using any type of equipment to receive or record live television broadcasts or to use the BBC's streaming service, iPlayer.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The fee is set by the British government, agreed by Parliament, and is used to fund the BBC's radio, TV, and online services covering the nations and regions of the UK.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Since 1 April 2014, it has also funded the BBC World Service (launched in 1932 as the BBC Empire Service), which broadcasts in 43 languages as of 2026.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Some of the BBC's revenue comes from its commercial subsidiary BBC Studios (formerly BBC Worldwide), which sells BBC programs and services internationally and also distributes the BBC's international 24-hour English-language news services BBC News, and from BBC.com, provided by BBC Global News Ltd.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Since its formation on 18 October 1922, the BBC has played a prominent role in British life and culture.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] It is sometimes informally referred to as **the Beeb** or **Auntie**.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1923 it launched *Radio Times* (subtitled "The official organ of the BBC"), the first broadcast listings magazine; the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11 million copies, the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Britain's first live public broadcast was made from the factory of Marconi Company in Chelmsford in June 1920.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] It was sponsored by the *Daily Mail*'s Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe and featured the famous Australian soprano Dame Nellie Melba.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The Melba broadcast caught the people's imagination and marked a turning point in the British public's attitude to radio.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] However, this public enthusiasm was not shared in official circles where such broadcasts were held to interfere with important military and civil communications.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] By late 1920, the pressure from these quarters and uneasiness among the staff of the licensing authority, the General Post Office (GPO), was sufficient to lead to a ban on further Chelmsford broadcasts.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] But by 1922 the GPO had received nearly 100 broadcast licence requests and moved to rescind its ban in the wake of a petition by 63 wireless societies with over 3,000 members.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] John Reith, a Scottish Calvinist, was appointed its general manager in December 1922 a few weeks after the company made its first official broadcast.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Stanton Jefferies was its first director of music.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The company was to be financed by a royalty on the sale of BBC wireless receiving sets from approved domestic manufacturers.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] To this day, the BBC aims to follow the Reithian directive to "inform, educate and entertain".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The financial arrangements soon proved inadequate.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Set sales were disappointing as amateurs made their own receivers and listeners bought rival unlicensed sets.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] By mid-1923, discussions between the GPO and the BBC had become deadlocked and the Postmaster General commissioned a review of broadcasting by the Sykes Committee.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The committee recommended a short-term reorganisation of licence fees with improved enforcement to address the BBC's immediate financial distress, and an increased share of the licence revenue split between it and the GPO.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] This was to be followed by a simple 10 shillings licence fee to fund broadcasts.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC's broadcasting monopoly was made explicit for the duration of its current broadcast licence, as was the prohibition on advertising.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] To avoid competition with newspapers, Fleet Street persuaded the government to ban news bulletins before 7 pm and the BBC was required to source all news from external wire services.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The *Radio Times*, the world's first and longest-running radio and television listings magazine, was launched by Reith in September 1923.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The first edition, subtitled "The official organ of the BBC", was priced at tuppence (two pence) on newsstands, and quickly sold out its run of a quarter of a million copies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Mid-1925 found the future of broadcasting under further consideration, this time by the Crawford committee.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] By now the BBC, under Reith's leadership, had forged a consensus favouring a continuation of the unified (monopoly) broadcasting service, but more money was still required to finance rapid expansion.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Wireless manufacturers were anxious to exit the loss-making consortium, and Reith was keen that the BBC be seen as a public service rather than a commercial enterprise.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The recommendations of the Crawford Committee were published in March the following year and were still under consideration by the GPO when the 1926 United Kingdom general strike broke out in May.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The strike temporarily interrupted newspaper production, and with restrictions on news bulletins waived, the BBC suddenly became the primary source of news for the duration of the crisis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The crisis placed the BBC in a delicate position.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On the one hand Reith was acutely aware that the government might exercise its right to commandeer the BBC at any time as a mouthpiece of the government if the BBC were to step out of line, but on the other he was anxious to maintain public trust by appearing to be acting independently.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The government was divided on how to handle the BBC, but ended up trusting Reith, whose opposition to the strike mirrored the PM's own.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Although Winston Churchill in particular wanted to commandeer the BBC to use it "to the best possible advantage", Reith wrote that Stanley Baldwin's government wanted to be able to say "that they did not commandeer [the BBC], but they know that they can trust us not to be really impartial".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Thus the BBC was granted sufficient leeway to pursue the government's objectives largely in a manner of its own choosing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Supporters of the strike nicknamed the BBC the BFC for British Falsehood Company.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Reith personally announced the end of the strike which he marked by reciting from Blake's "Jerusalem" signifying that England had been saved.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] While the BBC tends to characterise its coverage of the general strike by emphasising the positive impression created by its balanced coverage of the views of government and strikers, Seaton has characterised the episode as the invention of "modern propaganda in its British form".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Reith argued that trust gained by 'authentic impartial news' could then be used.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Impartial news was not necessarily an end in itself.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The British Broadcasting Corporation came into existence on 1 January 1927, and Reith – newly knighted – was appointed its first director general.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] To represent its purpose and (stated) values, the new corporation adopted the coat of arms, including the motto "Nation shall speak peace unto Nation".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] British radio audiences had little choice apart from BBC's programming approach.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Reith was viewed as taking a moralistic approach as an executive, aiming to broadcast "all that is best in every department of human knowledge, endeavour and achievement", and putting the programming in moral or ethical terms, advocating "a high moral tone" as "obviously of paramount importance".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Reith succeeded in building a high wall against a more tabloid, free-for-all in radio aimed at merely attracting the largest audience (and advertising revenue).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] There was no paid advertising on the BBC; all the revenue came from a tax on receiving sets.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Highbrow audiences, however, greatly enjoyed it.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] At a time when American, Australian and Canadian stations were drawing huge audiences cheering for their local teams with the broadcast of baseball, rugby and hockey, the BBC emphasised service for a national rather than a regional audience.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Boat races were well covered along with tennis and horse racing, but the BBC was reluctant to spend its severely limited air time on long football or cricket games, regardless of their popularity.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] John Reith and the BBC, with support from the Crown, determined the universal needs of the people of Britain and broadcast content according to these perceived standards.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Reith effectively censored anything that he felt would be harmful, directly or indirectly.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] While recounting his time with the BBC in 1935, Raymond Postgate claims that BBC broadcasters were made to submit a draft of their potential broadcast for approval.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] It was expected that they tailored their content to accommodate the modest, church-going elderly or a member of the Clergy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Until 1928, entertainers broadcasting on the BBC, both singers and "talkers" were expected to avoid biblical quotations, Clerical impersonations and references, references to drink or Prohibition in the United States, vulgar and doubtful matter and political allusions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC excluded popular foreign music and musicians from its broadcasts, while promoting British alternatives.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 5 March 1928, Stanley Baldwin, the Prime Minister, maintained the censorship of editorial opinions on public policy, but allowed the BBC to address matters of religious, political or industrial controversy.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The resulting political "talk series", designed to inform England on political issues, were criticised by members of parliament, including Winston Churchill, David Lloyd George and Sir Austen Chamberlain.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Those who opposed these chats claimed that they silence the opinions of those in Parliament who are not nominated by Party Leaders or Party Whips, thus stifling independent, non-official views.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In October 1932, the policemen of the Metropolitan Police Federation marched in protest at a proposed pay cut.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Fearing dissent within the police force and public support for the movement, the BBC censored its coverage of the events, only broadcasting official statements from the government.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Throughout the 1930s political broadcasts had been monitored by the BBC.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1935, the BBC censored the broadcasts of Oswald Mosley and Harry Pollitt.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Mosley was a leader of the British Union of Fascists, and Pollitt a leader of the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] They were contracted to provide a series of five broadcasts on their parties' politics.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC, in conjunction with The Foreign Office of Britain, suspended this series and ultimately cancelled it without the notice of the public.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1938, Winston Churchill proposed a series of talks regarding British domestic and foreign politics and affairs but was censored.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The censorship of political discourse by the BBC started the shutdown of the political debate that manifested over the BBC's wartime airwaves.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The Foreign Office maintained that the public should not be aware of their role in the censorship.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] From 1935 to 1939, the BBC attempted to unite the British Empire's radio waves, sending staff to Egypt, Palestine, Newfoundland, Jamaica, India, Canada and South Africa.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Reith visited South Africa, lobbying for state-run radio programmes accepted by South African Parliament in 1936.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] A similar programme was adopted in Canada.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Through collaboration with these state-run broadcasting centres, Reith had an influence on the culture across the empire of Great Britain with his departure from the corporation in 1938.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Experimental television broadcasts were started in 1929 using an electromechanical 30-line system developed by John Logie Baird.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The superiority of the electronic system saw the mechanical system dropped early the following year, with the Marconi-EMI system the first fully electronic television system in the world to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The success of broadcasting provoked animosities between the BBC and well-established media such as theatres, concert halls and the recording industry.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] By 1929, the BBC complained that the agents of many comedians refused to sign contracts for broadcasting, because they feared it harmed the artist "by making his material stale" and that it "reduces the value of the artist as a visible music-hall performer".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Television broadcasting was suspended from 1 September 1939 to 7 June 1946, during World War II, and it was left to BBC Radio broadcasters such as Reginald Foort to keep the nation's spirits up.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC moved most of its radio operations out of London, initially to Bristol, and then to Bedford.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] BBC employees during the war included George Orwell who spent two years with the broadcaster.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] During his role as prime minister during the war, Winston Churchill delivered 33 major wartime speeches by radio, all of which were carried by the BBC within the UK.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 18 June 1940, French general Charles de Gaulle, in exile in London as the leader of the Free French, made a speech, broadcast by the BBC, urging the French people not to capitulate to the Nazis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In October 1940, Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret made their first radio broadcast for the BBC's *Children's Hour*, addressing other children who had been evacuated from cities.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1938 John Reith and the Government of the United Kingdom, specifically the Ministry of Information which had been set up for WWII, designed a censorship apparatus for the inevitability of war.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Due to the BBC's advancements in shortwave radio technology, the corporation could broadcast across the world during the Second World War.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Within Europe, the BBC European Service would gather intelligence and information regarding the current events of the war in English.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Regional BBC workers, based on their regional geo-political climate, would then further censor the material their broadcasts would cover.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Nothing was to be added outside the preordained news items.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] For example, the BBC Polish Service was heavily censored due to fears of jeopardising relations with the Soviet Union.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Controversial topics, i.e. the contested Polish and Soviet border, the deportation of Polish citizens, the arrests of Polish Home Army members and the Katyn massacre, were not included in Polish broadcasts.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] American radio broadcasts were broadcast across Europe on BBC channels.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] This material also passed through the BBC's censorship office, which surveilled and edited American coverage of British affairs.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] By 1940, across all BBC broadcasts, music by composers from enemy nations was censored.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In total, 99 German, 38 Austrian and 38 Italian composers were censored.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC argued that like the Italian or German languages, listeners would be irritated by the inclusion of enemy composers.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Any potential broadcasters said to have pacifist, communist or fascist ideologies were not allowed on the BBC's airwaves.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1937, a MI5 security officer was given a permanent office within the organisation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] This officer would examine the files of potential political subversives and mark the files of those deemed a security risk to the organisation, blacklisting them.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] This was often done on spurious grounds; even so, the practice would continue and expand during the years of the Cold War.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] There was a widely reported urban myth that, upon resumption of the BBC television service after the war, announcer Leslie Mitchell started by saying, "As I was saying before we were so rudely interrupted ...".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In fact, the first person to appear when transmission resumed was Jasmine Bligh and the words said were, "Good afternoon, everybody.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Do you remember me, Jasmine Bligh...?" The European Broadcasting Union was formed on 12 February 1950, in Torquay with the BBC among the 23 founding broadcasting organizations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Competition to the BBC was introduced in 1955, with the commercial and independently operated television network of Independent Television (ITV).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] However, the BBC monopoly on radio services would persist until 8 October 1973 when under the control of the newly renamed Independent Broadcasting Authority (IBA), the UK's first Independent local radio station, LBC came on-air in the London area.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] BBC2 used the higher resolution 625-line standard which had been standardised across Europe.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] BBC2 was broadcast in colour from 1 July 1967 and was joined by BBC1 and ITV on 15 November 1969.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The 405-line VHF transmissions of BBC1 (and ITV) were continued for compatibility with older television receivers until 1985.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Starting in 1964, a series of pirate radio stations (starting with Radio Caroline) came on the air and forced the British government finally to regulate radio services to permit nationally based advertising-financed services.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In response, the BBC reorganised and renamed their radio channels.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 30 September 1967, the Light Programme was split into Radio 1 offering continuous "Popular" music and Radio 2 more "Easy Listening".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The "Third" programme became Radio 3 offering classical music and cultural programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The Home Service became Radio 4 offering news, and non-musical content such as quiz shows, readings, dramas and plays.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] As well as the four national channels, a series of local BBC radio stations were established in 1967, including Radio London.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1969, the BBC Enterprises department was formed to exploit BBC brands and programmes for commercial spin-off products.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1979, it became a wholly owned limited company, BBC Enterprises Ltd.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1974 the BBC's teletext service, Ceefax, was introduced, created initially to provide subtitling, but developed into a news and information service.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1978, BBC staff went on strike just before the Christmas, thus blocking out the transmission of both channels and amalgamating all four radio stations into one.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Since the deregulation of the UK television and radio market in the 1980s, the BBC has faced increased competition from the commercial sector (and from the advertiser-funded public service broadcaster Channel 4), especially on satellite television, cable television, and digital television services.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In the late 1980s, the BBC began a process of divestment by spinning off and selling parts of its organisation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1988, it sold off the Hulton Press Library, a photographic archive which had been acquired from the *Picture Post* magazine by the BBC in 1957.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The archive was sold to Brian Deutsch and is now owned by Getty Images.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1987, the BBC decided to centralise its operations by the management team with the radio and television divisions joining forces together for the first time, the activities of the news and currents departments and coordinated jointly under the new directorate.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] During the 1990s, this process continued with the separation of certain operational arms of the corporation into autonomous but wholly owned subsidiaries, with the aim of generating additional revenue for programme-making.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] BBC Enterprises was reorganised and relaunched in 1995, as BBC Worldwide Ltd.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1998, BBC studios, outside broadcasts, post production, design, costumes and wigs were spun off into BBC Resources Ltd.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC Research & Development has played a major part in the development of broadcasting and recording techniques.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC was also responsible for the development of the NICAM stereo standard.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The new station would be a news and sport station.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1997, BBC News 24, a rolling news channel, launched on digital television services, and the following year, BBC Choice was launched as the third general entertainment channel from the BBC.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC also purchased The Parliamentary Channel, which was renamed BBC Parliament.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1999, BBC Knowledge launched as a multimedia channel, with services available on the newly launched BBC Text digital teletext service (later rebranded as BBC Red Button), and on BBC Online.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The channel had an educational aim, which was modified later on in its life to offer documentaries.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 2002 several television and radio channels were reorganised.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] BBC Knowledge was replaced by BBC Four and became the BBC's arts and documentaries channel.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] CBBC, which had been a programming strand as Children's BBC since 1985, was split into CBBC and CBeebies, for younger children, with both new services getting a digital channel: the CBBC Channel and CBeebies Channel.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In addition to the television channels, new digital radio stations were created: 1Xtra, 6 Music and Radio 4 Extra.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] BBC 1Xtra was a sister station to Radio 1 and specialised in modern black music, BBC 6 Music specialised in alternative music genres and BBC7 specialised in archive, speech and children's programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 2008, another channel was launched, BBC Alba, a Scottish Gaelic service.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 2006 BBC HD was launched as an experimental service, becoming official in December 2007.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The channel broadcast HD simulcasts of programmes on BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Three and BBC Four as well as repeats of some older programmes in HD.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 2010, an HD simulcast of BBC One launched: BBC One HD.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The channel uses HD versions of BBC One's schedule and uses upscaled versions of programmes not currently produced in HD.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC HD channel closed in March 2013 and was replaced by BBC Two HD in the same month.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The 2004 Hutton Inquiry and the subsequent report raised questions about the BBC's journalistic standards and its impartiality.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] This led to resignations of senior management members at the time including the then Director General, Greg Dyke.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In January 2007, the BBC released minutes of the board meeting which led to Greg Dyke's resignation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC's IT, telephony and broadcast technology were brought together as BBC Technology Ltd in 2001, and the division was later sold to the German company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] SIS was subsequently acquired from Siemens by the French company Atos.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Further divestments included BBC Books (sold to Random House in 2006); BBC Outside Broadcasts Ltd (sold in 2008 to Satellite Information Services); Costumes and Wigs (stock sold in 2008 to Angels Costumes); and BBC Magazines (sold to Immediate Media Company in 2011).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] After the sales of OBs and costumes, the remainder of BBC Resources was reorganised as BBC Studios and Post Production, which continues today as a wholly owned subsidiary of the BBC.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] A strike in May 2005 by more than 11,000 BBC workers over a proposal to cut 4,000 jobs and to privatise parts of the BBC, disrupted much of the BBC's regular programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The blueprint for the future of the BBC resulting from the project was published ion 25 April 2006.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 18 October 2007, Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures", which included merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The plans included a reduction in posts of 2,500; including 1,800 redundancies, consolidating news operations, reducing programming output by 10% and selling off the flagship Television Centre building in London.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 20 October 2010 the Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne announced that the television licence fee would be frozen at its current level until the end of the current charter in 2016.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The same announcement revealed that the BBC would take on the full cost of running the BBC World Service and the BBC Monitoring service from the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office, and partially finance the Welsh broadcaster S4C.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] BBC HD was closed on 26 March 2013, and replaced with an HD simulcast of BBC Two; however, flagship programmes, other channels and full funding for CBBC and CBeebies would be retained.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Numerous BBC facilities have been sold off, including New Broadcasting House on Wilmslow Road in Manchester.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Many major departments have been relocated to Broadcasting House in central London and MediaCityUK in Salford, particularly since the closure of BBC Television Centre in March 2013.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 16 February 2016, the BBC Three television service was discontinued and replaced by a digital outlet under the same name, targeting its young adult audience with web series and other content.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Under the new royal charter instituted in 2017, the corporation must publish an annual report to Ofcom, outlining its plans and public service obligations for the next year.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In its 2017–18 report, released July 2017, the BBC announced plans to "re-invent" its output to better compete against commercial streaming services such as Netflix.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Since 2017, the BBC has also funded the Local Democracy Reporting Service, with up to 165 journalists employed by independent news organisations to report on local democracy issues on a pooled basis.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 2016 the BBC Director General Tony Hall announced a savings target of £800 million per year by 2021, which is about 23% of annual licence fee revenue.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Having to take on the £700 million cost for free TV licences for the over-75 pensioners, and rapid inflation in drama and sport coverage costs, was given as the reason.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Duplication of management and content spending would be reduced, and there would be a review of BBC News.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In September 2019 the BBC launched the Trusted News Initiative to work with news and social media companies to combat disinformation about national elections.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 520 staff reductions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC's director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 2020, the BBC reported a £119 million deficit because of delays to cost reduction plans, and the forthcoming ending of the remaining £253 million funding towards pensioner licence fees would increase financial pressures.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In March 2023 the BBC was at the centre of a political row with football pundit Gary Lineker, after he criticised the British government's asylum policy on social media.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Lineker was suspended from his position on *Match of the Day* before being re-instated after receiving overwhelming support from his colleagues.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The scandal was made worse due to the connections between BBC's chairman, Richard Sharp, and the Conservative Party.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In April 2023 Richard Sharp resigned as chairman after a report found he did not disclose potential perceived conflicts of interest in his role in the facilitation of a loan to Prime Minister Boris Johnson.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Dame Elan Closs Stephens was appointed as acting chairwoman on 27 June 2023, and she would lead the BBC board for a year or until a new permanent chair has been appointed.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Samir Shah was subsequently appointed with effect from 4 March 2024.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In October 2024 it was announced that the BBC along with Sky Sports signed a deal to broadcast the 2025–26 season of the Women's Super League campaign.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In May 2025, BBC director general Tim Davie said there were plans to switch off traditional broadcast transmissions in the 2030s to transition to a fully online delivery of programmes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In November 2025, following the leaking of a report that alleged systemic bias within the BBC, Tim Davie resigned as Director-General along with Deborah Turness as CEO of News within the organisation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 16 December 2025, the UK government considered a green paper of new ways to fund the BBC, such as replacing the television licence with either advertising or a subscription model.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 25 March 2026, former Google executive Matt Brittin was appointed as the new Director-General.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] On 15 April 2026, BBC announced cuts up to 2,000 jobs—its largest layoffs in over a decade—to reduce costs by about 10% (around £500 million) over the next two years.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC is a chartered corporation, independent from direct government intervention, with its activities being overseen from April 2017 by the BBC Board and regulated by Ofcom.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC is a public broadcasting company that operates under a royal charter.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The charter is the constitutional basis for the BBC, and sets out the BBC's object, mission and public purposes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] It emphasises public service, (limited) editorial independence, prohibits advertising on domestic services and proclaims the BBC is to "seek to avoid adverse impacts on competition which are not necessary for the effective fulfilment of the Mission and the promotion of the Public Purposes".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The charter additionally sets out that the BBC is subject to an additional agreement between it and the Culture Secretary, and that its operating licence is to be set by Ofcom, an external regulatory body.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] It used to be that the Home Secretary be departmental to both the agreement as well as the licence, and regulatory duties fall to the BBC Trust, but the 2017 charter changed those 2007 arrangements.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The charter also outlines the BBC's governance and regulatory arrangements as a statutory corporation, including the role and composition of the BBC Board.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The current charter took effect on 1 January 2017 and is set to expire on 31 December 2027; the agreement being coterminous.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] It replaced the previous governing body, the BBC Trust, which itself had replaced the board of governors in 2007.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The board sets the strategy for the corporation, assesses the performance of the BBC's executive board in delivering the BBC's services, and appoints the director-general.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Ofcom is responsible for the regulation of the BBC.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Samir Shah has served as the chairman since 4 March 2024.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The executive committee is responsible for the day-to-day operations of the broadcaster.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Consisting of senior managers of the BBC, the committee meets once per month and is responsible for operational management and delivery of services within a framework set by the board, and is chaired by the director-general, who is chief executive and (from 1994) editor-in-chief.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] From as early as the 1930s until the 1990s, MI5, the British domestic intelligence service, engaged in the vetting of applicants for BBC jobs, a policy designed to keep out persons deemed subversive.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1933, BBC executive Colonel Alan Dawnay began to meet the head of MI5, Sir Vernon Kell, to informally trade information; from 1935, a formal arrangement was made whereby job applicants would be secretly vetted by MI5 for their political views (without their knowledge).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] The BBC took up a policy of denying any suggestion by the press of such a relationship (the very existence of MI5 itself was not officially acknowledged until the Security Service Act 1989).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] This relationship garnered wider public attention after an article by David Leigh and Paul Lashmar appeared in *The Observer* in August 1985, revealing that MI5 had been vetting appointments, running operations from Room 105 in Broadcasting House.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] At the time of the exposé, the operation was being run by Ronnie Stonham.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] A memo from 1984 revealed that blacklisted organisations included the far-left Communist Party of Great Britain, the Socialist Workers Party, the Workers Revolutionary Party and the Militant tendency, as well as the far-right National Front and the British National Party.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] An association with one of these groups could result in a denial of a job application.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In October 1985 the BBC announced that it would stop the vetting process, except for a few people in top roles, as well as those in charge of Wartime Broadcasting Service emergency broadcasting (in the event of a nuclear war) and staff of the BBC World Service.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] In 1990, following the Security Service Act 1989, vetting was further restricted to those responsible for wartime broadcasting and those with access to secret government information.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p01] Michael Hodder, who succeeded Stonham, had the MI5 vetting files sent to the BBC Archives in Reading, Berkshire.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC has the second largest budget of any UK-based broadcaster with an operating expenditure of £4.722 billion in 2013/14 compared with £6.471 billion for Sky UK in 2013/14 and £1.843 billion for ITV in the calendar year 2013.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The principal means of funding the BBC is through the television licence, costing £169.50 per year per household as of April 2024.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Such a licence is required to legally receive broadcast television across the UK, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] No licence is required to own a television used for other means, or for sound only radio sets (though a separate licence for these was also required for non-TV households until 1971).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The cost of a television licence is set by the government and enforced by the criminal law.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] A 50% discount is offered to people who are registered blind or severely visually impaired, and the licence is completely free for any household containing anyone aged 75 or over and receiving pension credit.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC pursues its licence fee collection and enforcement under the trading name "TV Licensing".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The revenue is collected privately by Capita, an outside agency, and is paid into the central government Consolidated Fund, a process defined in the Communications Act 2003.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Funds are then allocated by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) and the Treasury and approved by Parliament via legislation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Additional revenues are paid by the Department for Work and Pensions to compensate for subsidised licences for eligible over-75-year-olds.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The licence fee is classified as a tax, and its evasion is a criminal offence.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Since 1991, collection and enforcement of the licence fee has been the responsibility of the BBC in its role as TV Licensing Authority.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC carries out surveillance (mostly using subcontractors) on properties (under the auspices of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000) and may conduct searches of a property using a search warrant.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] According to TV Licensing, 216,900 people in the UK were caught watching TV without a licence in 2018/19.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Licence fee evasion makes up about one-tenth of all cases prosecuted in magistrates' courts, representing 0.3% of court time.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Income from commercial enterprises and from overseas sales of its catalogue of programmes has substantially increased over recent years, with BBC Worldwide contributing some £243 million to the BBC's core public service business.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] But the licence fee has attracted criticism.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It has been argued that in an age of multi-stream, multi-channel availability, an obligation to pay a licence fee is no longer appropriate.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC's use of private sector company Capita to send letters to premises not paying the licence fee has been criticised, especially as there have been cases where such letters have been sent to premises which are up to date with their payments, or do not require a TV licence.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC uses advertising campaigns to inform customers of the requirement to pay the licence fee.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Past campaigns have been criticised by Conservative MP Boris Johnson and former MP Ann Widdecombe for having a threatening nature and language used to scare evaders into paying.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Audio clips and television broadcasts are used to inform listeners of the BBC's comprehensive database.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] There are a number of pressure groups campaigning on the issue of the licence fee.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In 2023, about half a million UK households cancelled their TV licence, driven by shifting viewing habits and financial pressures.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] As a result, the BBC saw a decline in revenue, with the number of households paying the licence fee dropping to 23.9 million.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The majority of the BBC's commercial output comes from its commercial arm BBC Worldwide which sell programmes abroad and exploit key brands for merchandise.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In April 2026, the BBC announced that they would be cutting between 1,800 and 2,000 jobs, citing a need to save £500 million over the coming two years.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House in Portland Place, central London, is the official headquarters of the BBC.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It is also the home of BBC News, which relocated to the building from BBC Television Centre in 2013.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] On the front of the building are statues of Prospero and Ariel, characters from William Shakespeare's play *The Tempest*, sculpted by Eric Gill.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Renovation of Broadcasting House began in 2002, and was completed in 2012.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Until it closed at the end of March 2013, BBC Television was based at Television Centre, a purpose-built television facility opened in 1960 located in White City, four miles (6 km) west of central London.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] This facility was host to a number of famous guests and programmes through the years, and its name and image is familiar with many British citizens.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Nearby, the White City Place complex contains numerous programme offices, housed in Centre House, the Media Centre and Broadcast Centre.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It is in this area around Shepherd's Bush that the majority of BBC employees worked.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] As part of a major reorganisation of BBC property, the entire BBC News operation relocated from the News Centre at BBC Television Centre to the refurbished Broadcasting House to create what is being described as "one of the world's largest live broadcast centres".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC News Channel and BBC News International relocated to the premises in early 2013.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House is now also home to most of the BBC's national radio stations, and the BBC World Service.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The major part of this plan involved the demolition of the two post-war extensions to the building and construction of an extension designed by Sir Richard MacCormac of MJP Architects.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] This move concentrated the BBC's London operations, allowing them to sell Television Centre.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] As well as the two main sites in London (Broadcasting House and White City), there are seven other important BBC production centres in the UK, mainly specialising in different productions.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Cardiff is home to BBC Cymru Wales, which specialises in drama production.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Open since 2012, and containing 7 new studios, Roath Lock is notable as the home of productions such as *Doctor Who* and *Casualty*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House Belfast, home to BBC Northern Ireland, specialises in original drama and comedy, and has taken part in many co-productions with independent companies and notably with RTÉ in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Scotland, based in Pacific Quay, Glasgow is a large producer of programmes for the network, including several quiz shows.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In England, the larger regions also produce some programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Previously the largest hub of BBC programming from the regions had been BBC North West.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] At present they produce all religious and ethical programmes on the BBC, as well as other programmes such as *A Question of Sport*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] However, this is to be merged and expanded under the BBC North project, which involved the region moving from New Broadcasting House, Manchester, to MediaCityUK.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Midlands, based at Mailbox Birmingham, also produces drama and contains the headquarters for the English regions and the BBC's daytime output.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Other production centres include Broadcasting House Bristol, home of BBC West and famously the BBC Studios Natural History Unit and to a lesser extent, Quarry Hill in Leeds, home of BBC Yorkshire.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] There are also many smaller local and regional studios throughout the UK, operating the BBC regional television services and the BBC Local Radio stations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates several news gathering centres in various locations around the world, which provide news coverage of that region to the national and international news operations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In 2004 the BBC contracted out its former BBC Technology division to the German engineering and electronics company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS), outsourcing its IT, telephony and broadcast technology systems.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] When Atos Origin acquired the SIS division from Siemens in December 2010 for €850 million (£720m), the BBC support contract also passed to Atos, and in July 2011, the BBC announced to staff that its technology support would become an Atos service.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Siemens staff working on the BBC contract were transferred to Atos; the BBC's Information Technology systems are now managed by Atos.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In 2012, the BBC's then-chief technology officer John Linwood, expressed confidence in service improvements to the BBC's technology provision brought about by Atos.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] He also stated that supplier accountability had been strengthened following some high-profile technology failures which had taken place during the partnership with Siemens.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC operates several television channels nationally and internationally.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC One and BBC Two are the flagship television channels.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Others include the youth channel BBC Three, cultural and documentary channel BBC Four, the British and international variations of the BBC News channel, parliamentary channel BBC Parliament, and two children's channels, CBBC and CBeebies.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Digital television is now entrenched in the UK, with analogue transmission completely phased out as of December 2012.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC One is a regionalised TV service which provides opt-outs throughout the day for local news and other local programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] These variations are more pronounced in the BBC "Nations", i.e.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales, where the presentation is mostly carried out locally on BBC One and Two, and where programme schedules can vary considerably from that of the network.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Two variations exist in the Nations; however, English regions today rarely have the option to opt out as regional programming now exists only on BBC One.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In 2019, the Scottish variation of BBC Two ceased operation and was replaced with the networked version in favour of a new BBC Scotland channel.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Two was the first channel to be transmitted on 625 lines, in 1964.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It then carried a small-scale regular colour service from 1967.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] A new Scottish Gaelic television channel, BBC Alba, was launched in September 2008.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It is also the first multi-genre channel to come entirely from Scotland with almost all of its programmes made in Scotland.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The service was initially available only via satellite but since June 2011 has been available to viewers in Scotland on Freeview and cable television.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC currently operates HD simulcasts of all its nationwide channels with the exception of BBC Parliament.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Until 26 March 2013, a separate channel called BBC HD was available, in place of BBC Two HD.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It launched on 15 May 2006, following a 12-month trial of the broadcasts.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It became a proper channel in 2007, and screened HD programmes as simulcasts of the main network, or as repeats.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The corporation has been producing programmes in the format for many years, and stated that it hoped to produce 100% of new programmes in HDTV by 2010.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] On 3 November 2010, a high-definition simulcast of BBC One was launched, entitled BBC One HD, and BBC Two HD launched on 26 March 2013, replacing BBC HD.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Scotland's new television channel, BBC Scotland, launched in February 2019.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In the Republic of Ireland, Belgium, the Netherlands and Switzerland, the BBC channels are available in a number of ways.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In these countries digital and cable operators carry a range of BBC channels.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Since 1975 the BBC has also provided its TV programmes to the British Forces Broadcasting Service (BFBS), allowing members of UK military serving abroad to watch them on four dedicated TV channels.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] From 27 March 2013, BFBS will carry versions of BBC One and BBC Two, which will include children's programming from CBBC, as well as carrying programming from BBC Three on a new channel called BFBS Extra.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Since 2008 all BBC channels are available to watch online through the BBC iPlayer service.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] This online streaming ability came about following experiments with live streaming, involving streaming certain channels in the UK.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In February 2014, Director-General Tony Hall announced that the corporation needed to save £100 million.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In March 2014, the BBC confirmed plans for BBC Three to become an internet-only channel.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] An earlier ten months of listings are to be obtained from other sources.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] They identified about five million programmes, involving 8.5 million actors, presenters, writers and technical staff.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The Genome project was opened to public access on 15 October 2014, with corrections to OCR errors and changes to advertised schedules being crowdsourced.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC has ten radio stations serving the whole of the UK, a further seven stations in the "national regions" (Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland), and 39 other local stations serving defined areas of England.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Of the ten national stations, five are major stations and are available on FM or AM as well as on DAB and online.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In addition to these five stations, the BBC runs a further five stations that broadcast on DAB and online only.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] These stations supplement and expand on the big five stations, and were launched in 2002.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1Xtra sisters Radio 1, and broadcasts new Black music and urban tracks.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 5 Sports Extra sisters 5 Live and offers extra sport analysis, including broadcasting sports that previously were not covered.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 6 Music offers alternative music genres and is notable as a platform for new artists.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 7, later renamed BBC Radio 4 Extra, provides archive drama, comedy and children's programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The final station is the BBC Asian Network, providing music, talk and news to this section of the community.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] This station evolved out of Local radio stations serving certain areas, and as such this station is available on medium wave frequency in some areas of the Midlands.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] As well as the national stations, the BBC also provides 40 BBC Local Radio stations in England and the Channel Islands, each named for and covering a particular city and its surrounding area (e.g.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Bristol), county or region (e.g.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Three Counties Radio), or geographical area (e.g.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Solent covering the central south coast).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] A further six stations broadcast in what the BBC terms "the national regions": Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] These are BBC Radio Wales (in English), BBC Radio Cymru (in Welsh), BBC Radio Scotland (in English), BBC Radio nan Gàidheal (in Scottish Gaelic), BBC Radio Ulster, and BBC Radio Foyle, the latter being an opt-out station from Radio Ulster for the north-west of Northern Ireland.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC's UK national channels are also broadcast in the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man (although these Crown Dependencies are outside the UK), and in the former there are two local stations – BBC Radio Guernsey and BBC Radio Jersey.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] There is no BBC local radio station, however, in the Isle of Man, partly because the island has long been served by the popular independent commercial station, Manx Radio, which predates the existence of BBC Local Radio.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC services in the dependencies are financed from television licence fees which are set at the same level as those payable in the UK, although collected locally.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] This is the subject of some controversy in the Isle of Man since, as well as having no BBC Local Radio service, the island also lacks a local television news service analogous to that provided by BBC Channel Islands.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It is broadcast worldwide on shortwave radio, DAB and online and has an estimated weekly audience of 192 million, and its websites have an audience of 38 million people per week.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Since 2005, it is also available on DAB in the UK, a step not taken before, due to the way it is funded.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Following the Government's spending review in 2011, the service was funded for the first time through the Licence fee.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In recent years, some services of the World Service have been reduced: the Thai service ended in 2006, as did the Eastern European languages.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Resources were diverted instead into the new BBC News Arabic.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Historically the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster based in the UK mainland until 1967, when University Radio York, then under the name *Radio York*, was launched as the first, and now oldest, legal independent radio station in the country.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] However, the BBC did not enjoy a complete monopoly before this, as several Continental stations, such as Radio Luxembourg, had broadcast programmes in English to Britain since the 1930s and the Isle of Man-based Manx Radio began in 1964.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Today, despite the advent of commercial broadcasting, BBC radio stations remain among the most listened-to in the country.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Radio 2 has the largest audience share (up to 16.8% in 2011–12) and Radios 1 and 4 ranked second and third in terms of weekly reach.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC programming is also available to other services and in other countries.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Since 1943, the BBC has provided radio programming to the British Forces Broadcasting Service, which broadcasts in countries where British troops are stationed.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1 is also carried in Canada on SiriusXM (online streaming only).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC is a patron of the Radio Academy, a registered UK charity that promotes excellence in broadcasting.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC News is the largest broadcast news gathering operation in the world, providing services to BBC domestic radio as well as television networks such as the BBC News, BBC Parliament and BBC News International.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In addition to this, news stories are available on the BBC Red Button service and BBC News Online.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In addition to this, the BBC has been developing new ways to access BBC News and as a result, has launched the service on BBC Mobile, making it accessible to mobile phones and PDAs, as well as developing alerts by email, on digital television, and on computers through a desktop alert.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Ratings figures suggest that during major incidents such as the 7 July 2005 London bombings or royal events, the UK audience overwhelmingly turns to the BBC's coverage as opposed to its commercial rivals.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] On 7 July 2005, the day there were a series of coordinated bomb blasts on London's public transport system, the BBC Online website recorded an all time bandwidth peak of 11 Gb/s at 12.00 on 7 July.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC News received some 1 billion total hits on the day of the event (including all images, text, and HTML), serving some 5.5 terabytes of data.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] At peak times during the day, there were 40,000-page requests per second for the BBC News website.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The previous day's announcement of the 2012 Summer Olympics being awarded to London caused a peak of about 5 Gbit/s.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The previous all-time high at BBC Online was caused by the announcement of the Michael Jackson verdict, which used 7.2 Gbit/s.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC's online presence includes a comprehensive news website and archive.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC's first official online service was the BBC Networking Club, which was launched on 11 May 1994.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The service was subsequently relaunched as BBC Online in 1997, before being renamed BBCi, then bbc.co.uk, before it was rebranded back as BBC Online.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The website is funded by the Licence fee, but uses GeoIP technology, allowing advertisements to be carried on the site when viewed outside of the UK.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC claims the site to be "Europe's most popular content-based site" and states that 13.2 million people in the UK visit the site's more than two million pages each day.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The centre of the website is the Homepage, which features a modular layout.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Users can choose which modules, and which information, is displayed on their homepage, allowing the user to customise it.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] This system was first launched in December 2007, becoming permanent in February 2008, and has undergone a few aesthetical changes since then.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The home page then has links to other micro-sites, such as BBC News Online, Sport, Weather, TV, and Radio.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] As part of the site, every programme on BBC Television or Radio is given its own page, with bigger programmes getting their own micro-site, and as a result it is often common for viewers and listeners to be told URLs for the programme website.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Also, through participation in the Creative Archive Licence group, bbc.co.uk allowed legal downloads of selected archive material via the internet.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC has often included learning as part of its online service, running services such as BBC Jam, Learning Zone Class Clips and also runs services such as BBC WebWise and First Click which are designed to teach people how to use the internet.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Jam was a free online service, delivered through broadband and narrowband connections, providing high-quality interactive resources designed to stimulate learning at home and at school.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Initial content was made available in January 2006; however, BBC Jam was suspended on 20 March 2007 due to allegations made to the European Commission that it was damaging the interests of the commercial sector of the industry.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In recent years some major on-line companies and politicians have complained that BBC Online receives too much funding from the television licence, meaning that other websites are unable to compete with the vast amount of advertising-free on-line content available on BBC Online.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Some have proposed that the amount of licence fee money spent on BBC Online should be reduced—either being replaced with funding from advertisements or subscriptions, or a reduction in the amount of content available on the site.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In response to this the BBC carried out an investigation, and has now set in motion a plan to change the way it provides its online services.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Online will now attempt to fill in gaps in the market, and will guide users to other websites for currently existing market provision.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] (For example, instead of providing local events information and timetables, users will be guided to outside websites already providing that information.) Part of this plan included the BBC closing some of its websites, and rediverting money to redevelop other parts.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] On 26 February 2010 *The Times* claimed that Mark Thompson, Director General of the BBC, proposed that the BBC's web output should be cut by 50%, with online staff numbers and budgets reduced by 25% in a bid to scale back BBC operations and allow commercial rivals more room.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] On 2 March 2010, the BBC reported that it would cut its website spending by 25% and close BBC 6 Music and Asian Network, as part of Mark Thompson's plans to make "a smaller, fitter BBC for the digital age".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Red Button is the brand name for the BBC's interactive television services, which are available through Freeview (digital terrestrial), as well as Freesat, Sky UK (satellite), and Virgin Media (cable).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Unlike Ceefax, the service's analogue counterpart, BBC Red Button is able to display full-colour graphics, photographs, and video, as well as programmes and can be accessed from any BBC channel.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The service carries News, Weather and Sport 24 hours a day, but also provides extra features related to programmes specific at that time.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Examples include viewers to play along at home to gameshows, to give, voice and vote on opinions to issues, as used alongside programmes such as *Question Time*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] At some points in the year, when multiple sporting events occur, some coverage of less mainstream sports or games are frequently placed on the Red Button for viewers to watch.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Frequently, other features are added unrelated to programmes being broadcast at that time, such as the broadcast of the *Doctor Who* animated episode *Dreamland* in November 2009.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It also buys a selected number of broadcasts from the Ulster Orchestra in Belfast and the BBC Big Band.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC Proms have been produced by the BBC every year since 1927, stepping in to fund the popular eight-week summer classical music festival when music publishers Chappell and Co withdrew their support.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In 1930, the newly formed BBC Symphony Orchestra gave all 49 Proms, and have performed at every Last Night of the Proms since then.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The Proms have been held at the Royal Albert Hall since 1941, and the BBC's orchestras and choirs are the backbone of the festival, giving about 40% to 50% of all performances each season.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Many famous musicians of every genre have played at the BBC, such as The Beatles (*Live at the BBC* is one of their many albums).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC is also responsible for the broadcast of Glastonbury Festival, Reading and Leeds Festivals and United Kingdom coverage of the Eurovision Song Contest, a show with which the broadcaster has been associated for over 60 years.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates the division of BBC Audiobooks sometimes found in association with Chivers Audiobooks.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC operates other ventures as well as its broadcasting arm.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In addition to broadcasting output on television and radio, some programmes are also displayed on the BBC Big Screens in several central-city locations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC and the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office also jointly run BBC Monitoring, which monitors radio, television, the press and the internet worldwide.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The National Museum of Computing at Bletchley Park uses BBC Micros as part of a scheme to educate school children about computer programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In 1951, in conjunction with Oxford University Press, the BBC published *The BBC Hymn Book*, intended to be used by radio listeners to follow hymns being broadcast.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The book was published both with and without music, the music edition being entitled *The BBC Hymn Book with Music*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC provided the world's first teletext service called Ceefax (near-homophonous with "See Facts") from 23 September 1974 until 23 October 2012 on the BBC1 analogue channel, then later on BBC2.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It showed informational pages, such as news, sport, and the weather.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] From New Year's Eve, 1974, ITV's Oracle tried to compete with Ceefax.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] During its lifetime, Ceefax attracted millions of viewers, right up until 2012, prior to the digital switchover in the United Kingdom.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Since then, the BBC's Red Button Service has provided a digital information system that replaced Ceefax.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In 2016 the BBC, in partnership with fellow UK broadcasters ITV and Channel 4 (the latter later withdrew from the project), set up 'project kangaroo' to develop an international online streaming service to rival services such as Netflix and Hulu.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] During the development stages 'Britflix' was touted as a potential name.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] However, the service eventually launched as BritBox in March 2017.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The online platform shows a catalogue of classic BBC and ITV shows, as well as making a number of programmes available shortly after their UK broadcast.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] As of 2021, BritBox is available in the UK, the US, Canada, Australia, and, more recently, South Africa, with the potential availability for new markets in the future.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Studios is the wholly owned commercial subsidiary of the BBC, responsible for the commercial exploitation of BBC programmes and other properties, including a number of television stations throughout the world.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It was formed in 2018 after the merger of the BBC's commercial production arm and the BBC's commercial international distribution arm, BBC Worldwide, with the latter formed in 1995 following the restructuring of its predecessor, BBC Enterprises.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Prior to this, the selling of BBC television programmes was at first handled in 1958 with the establishment of a business manager post.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] This expanded until the establishment of the Television Promotions (renamed Television Enterprises) department in 1960 under a general manager.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The company owns and administers a number of commercial stations around the world operating in a number of territories and on a number of different platforms.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] These include BBC UKTV for the Australasia region, and formerly BBC America (now fully owned by AMC Networks).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The company airs two channels aimed at children, an international CBeebies channel and BBC Kids, a joint venture with Knowledge Network Corporation.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The company also runs BBC Earth, which distributes the BBC's natural history content to countries outside the UK, and BBC Lifestyle, broadcasting programmes based on themes of Food, Style and Wellbeing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In addition to this, BBC Studios ran an international version of the channel BBC HD.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also distributes the 24-hour international news channel BBC News.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The station is separate from BBC Studios to maintain the station's neutral point of view, but is distributed by BBC Studios.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The channel itself is the oldest surviving entity of its kind, and has 50 foreign news bureaus and correspondents in nearly all countries in the world.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] As officially surveyed, it is available to more than 294 million households, significantly more than CNN's estimated 200 million.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In addition to these international channels, BBC Studios also owns the UKTV network of seven channels.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] These channels contain BBC archive programming to be rebroadcast on their respective channels: Alibi, crime dramas; Dave (slogan: "The Home of Witty Banter"); Drama, drama, launched in 2013; Eden, nature; Gold, comedy; W, Entertainment; and Yesterday, history programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In addition to these channels, many BBC programmes are sold via BBC Studios to foreign television stations with comedy, documentaries, crime dramas (such as *Luther* and *Peaky Blinders*) and historical drama productions being the most popular.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC's most successful reality television show format, *Strictly Come Dancing*—under the title *Dancing with the Stars*—has been exported to 60 other countries.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Shows commissioned and distributed by the BBC include the *Wallace & Gromit* animated comedy short films *The Wrong Trousers* and *A Close Shave*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC television news also appears nightly on many PBS stations in the US, as do reruns of BBC programmes such as *EastEnders*, and in New Zealand on TVNZ 1.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In addition to programming, BBC Studios produces material to accompany programmes.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The company maintained the publishing arm of the BBC, BBC Magazines, which published the *Radio Times*; first published by the BBC on 28 September 1923, it is the world's first broadcast listings magazine.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] *Radio Times* covers all British television and radio programming schedules, and the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11,220,666 copies, which the *Guinness World Records* certified as the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Other magazines that support BBC programming include *BBC Top Gear*, *BBC Good Food*, *BBC Sky at Night*, *BBC History*, *BBC Wildlife* and *BBC Music*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Magazines was sold to Exponent Private Equity in 2011, which merged it with Origin Publishing (previously owned by BBC Worldwide between 2004 and 2006) to form Immediate Media Company.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also publishes books, to accompany programmes such as *Sherlock* and *Doctor Who* under the BBC Books brand, a publishing imprint majority owned by Random House.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Archive programming and classical music recordings are sold under the brand BBC Legends.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Until the development, popularisation, and domination of television, radio was the broadcast medium upon which people in the United Kingdom relied.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It "reached into every home in the land, and simultaneously united the nation, an important factor during the Second World War".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC introduced the world's first "high-definition" 405-line television service in 1936.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It suspended its television service during the Second World War and until 1946, but remained the only television broadcaster in the UK until 1955, when Independent Television (ITV) began operating.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] This heralded the transformation of television into a popular and dominant medium.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Nevertheless, "throughout the 1950s radio still remained the dominant source of broadcast comedy".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Further, the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster until 1968 (when University Radio York obtained its first licence).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Despite the advent of commercial television and radio, with competition from ITV, Channel 4 and Sky, the BBC has remained one of the main elements in British popular culture through its obligation to produce TV and radio programmes for mass audiences.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] However, the arrival of BBC2 allowed the BBC also to make programmes for minority interests in drama, documentaries, current affairs, entertainment, and sport.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Described as television's first "watercooler moment" by *The Telegraph*, the BBC's 1954 adaptation of *Nineteen Eighty-Four* made a dramatic impact on a fledgling television audience who were horrified by the graphic depiction of a totalitarian regime controlling the population.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Making his BBC debut in 1949, Benny Hill with *The Benny Hill Show* became the first British comedian to become famous via television.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Popular comedy duos on the BBC include Morecambe and Wise (whose show debuted in 1968) and The Two Ronnies (debuting in 1971).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Black comedy sitcom *Blackadder*, starring Rowan Atkinson as the title character, ran for four series between 1983 and 1989.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The British Academy Film Awards (BAFTAs) was first broadcast on the BBC in 1956, with Vivien Leigh as the host.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The television equivalent, the British Academy Television Awards, has been screened exclusively on the BBC since a 2007 awards ceremony that included wins for Jim Broadbent (Best actor) and Ricky Gervais (Best comedy performance).
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The term "BBC English" was used as an alternative name for Received Pronunciation, and the *English Pronouncing Dictionary* uses the term "BBC Pronunciation" to label its recommendations.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] However, the BBC itself now makes more use of regional accents to reflect the diversity of the UK, while continuing to expect clarity and fluency of its presenters.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] From its "starchy" beginnings, the BBC has also become more inclusive, and now attempts to accommodate the interests of all strata of society and all minorities, because they all pay the licence fee.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Older domestic UK audiences often refer to the BBC as "the Beeb", a nickname coined by Peter Sellers during a 1972 reunion of the 1950s BBC radio comedy *The Goon Show*, when he referred to the "Beeb Beeb Ceeb".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It was then shortened and popularised by radio DJ Kenny Everett.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] David Bowie's recording sessions at the BBC were released as *Bowie at the Beeb*, while Queen's BBC recording sessions were released as *At the Beeb*.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The term "Auntie" for the BBC is often credited to radio disc-jockey Jack Jackson.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] To celebrate the fiftieth anniversary of the BBC the song "Auntie" was released in 1972.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It also featured in the title of the BBC's blooper show, *Auntie's Bloomers*, which was presented by Terry Wogan from 1991 to 2001.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The two nicknames have also been used together as "Auntie Beeb".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Throughout its existence the BBC has faced numerous accusations regarding many topics: the Iraq war, the Gaza war, politics, ethics and religion, as well as funding and staffing.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] It also has been involved in numerous controversies because of its coverage of specific news stories and programming.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC has been accused repeatedly of anti-Israel bias, and to a greater extent anti-Israel Defense Force bias.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] The BBC has long faced accusations of liberal and left-wing bias.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Accusations of a bias against the Premiership of Margaret Thatcher and the Conservative Party were often made against the BBC by members of that government, with Margaret Thatcher herself considering the broadcaster's news coverage to be biased and irresponsible.
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] In 2011, Peter Sissons, a main news presenter at the BBC from 1989 to 2009, said that "at the core of the BBC, in its very DNA, is a way of thinking that is firmly of the Left".
[src:egg-and-spoon-race/bbc-p02] Another BBC presenter, Andrew Marr, commented that "the BBC is not impartial or neutral.
